## Part One: Macro Men

## Chapter 1: Colm O'Shea — Knowing When It's Raining

### No Good War Stories
- O'Shea struggles to recall mistakes as learning experiences
- Best he can describe: missed profit opportunity
- **Wrong on 50%+ of trades** but never lets mistakes get close to "good story" territory
- Large trading losses incompatible with his methodology

### Global Macro Strategy Philosophy
- **Global macro trader**: profits from directional trends in global currency, interest rate, equity, commodity markets
- Views trading ideas as **hypotheses**
- Market move counter to expected direction = proof hypothesis is wrong
- No reluctance to liquidate position immediately upon invalidation
- Sizes positions so loss from invalidation point is limited to small % of assets
- Hence no dramatic loss stories

### Path to Economics and Trading

#### Early Intellectual Development
- Interest sequence: politics → economics → markets
- Teen years coincided with **Thatcherism** and national debate over government's economic role
- Self-educated in economics before university

#### First Economics Job (Pre-University)
- Consulting firm had abrupt opening for economist position
- Interview question: explain seeming paradox of **Keynesian multiplier**
  - "How does taking money from people by selling bonds and giving that same amount of money back to people through fiscal spending create stimulus?"
- O'Shea's honest response: **"That is a really good question. I never thought about it."**
- Admitted what he didn't know rather than bluffing—and was hired

#### Belgian Economy Forecast
- Firm made O'Shea the economist for Belgian economy (age 19)
- Picked up econometrics through independent reading
- Used firm's econometric models to derive forecasts
- Kept behind closed doors—not allowed to speak to clients
- O'Shea generated forecasts and wrote reports with minimal supervision

**Contrarian forecast insight:**
- General consensus: Belgium outlook negative
- After modeling, O'Shea concluded growth outlook "pretty good"
- Wanted forecast 2%+ higher than any other economist
- Firm: "You can't do that. This is how things work. We will allow you to have one of the highest forecasts, and if growth is really strong as you expect, we will still be right by having a forecast near the high end of the range. **There is nothing to be gained by having a forecast outside the range**, in which case if you are wrong, we would look ridiculous."
- O'Shea's forecast turned out right, but no one cared

> "As an economic consultant, how you package your work is more important than what you have actually done. There is massive herding in economic forecasting. By staying near the benchmark or the prevailing range, you get all the upside of being right without the downside."

### Key Lesson from Economic Consulting
- One-year stint taught O'Shea he did NOT want to be an economic consultant
- Understanding "rules of the game" made him cynical about economic forecasting

### Trading Career Progression
- **1992**: Graduated Cambridge, landed trader job at **Citigroup**
- Profitable every year with steadily increasing trading line and responsibilities
- **2003**: Left Citigroup to become portfolio manager for **Soros's Quantum Fund** (trading multibillion-dollar hedge fund exposure)
- **Two successful years at Soros**
- Left to become global macro strategy manager for multimanager fund at **Balyasny**
- **2007**: Formed own hedge fund, **COMAC**

### Performance Record
- **Never had a losing year**
- Majority of track record (Citigroup/Soros years) not available for public disclosure
- Only public portion: **Balyasny** (began Dec 2004) + current hedge fund **COMAC** (launched June 2006)
- **Combined period performance (Dec 2004 - end 2011):**
  - Average annual compounded net return: **11.3%**
  - Annualized volatility: **8.1%**
  - Worst monthly loss: **3.7%**

### Performance Evaluation: Return/Risk Matters

**Critical insight:**
- Return = function of both skill AND degree of risk taken
- Doubling risk will double return
- **True performance measure: return/risk, not return alone**
- Especially true for global macro (only fraction of assets typically required for portfolio positions)

**O'Shea's Risk Profile:**
- Runs fund at **relatively low risk level**
- Volatility (8.2%), worst monthly loss (3.7%), max drawdown (10.2%) = **~half the average for global macro managers**
- If run at exposure level matching majority of global macro managers (or volatility = S&P 500):
  - Average annual compounded return would be **~23%**
- If run as proprietary account (much higher exposure relative to assets):
  - Returns would be many times higher for exact same trading results

**Performance invariant to exposure level:**
- Discrepancies disappear when measured in return/risk terms
- **O'Shea's Gain to Pain ratio: strong 1.76**

### Interview Setting
- Conducted in London on royal wedding day (related street closures)
- Met at club with informal dress code
- Drawing room interview space, sparsely populated (most watching wedding)
- O'Shea spoke enthusiastically about economics, markets, trading
- At one point, another member asked O'Shea to speak more quietly
- O'Shea apologized, subsequently

