## Colm O'Shea Interview (continued)

### Origin Story: Finding Markets Through Literature

- **Age 17 in Rome**: O'Shea discovered *Reminiscences of a Stock Operator* at an open market — the only English book available
- The book brought "everything in my life together" — merged his interest in politics/economics with market dynamics

> "I disagree. It's all there. It starts off with the protagonist just reading the tape, but that isn't what makes him rich. Everyone gives him tips, but the character Mr. Partridge tells him all that matters, 'It's a bull market.'"

- **Key insight from the book**: There's a bigger picture beyond price movements — understanding whether it's a bull or bear market matters
- The protagonist becomes increasingly fundamental, focusing on demand and supply (core of global macro)

> "Price movements only have meaning in the context of the fundamental landscape. To use a sailing analogy, the wind matters, but the tide matters, too."

- Markets require both fundamentals and technicals — you can't just plan based on wind (technicals) and ignore tide (fundamentals)

### Economics Education and Its Failures

- Studied economics at **Cambridge** from age 12 interest, not as pathway to markets
- **Critical of modern economics education**: Has become about mathematical rigor and modeling rather than philosophy

> "The thing about mathematical modeling is that in order to make problems tractable, you need to make assumptions. Assumptions then become axiomatic for the entire subject—not because they are true, but because they are necessary to get a solution."

- **Example**: Efficient markets assumption — needed for math to work, but markets aren't actually efficient
- Mathematical models can't include speculators' unpredictable impact — would make equations unsolvable
- **Consequence**: Mathematization has driven real economists out into history, political science, sociology — "has been a disaster"

### Macro Philosophy: Keynes vs. Keynesianism

- **Favorite economist**: Keynes — but criticizes how Keynesianism has been distorted in US politics
- In US, "Keynesianism" wrongly means deficit spending regardless of economic cycle
- **True Keynesian view**: Keynes was a fiscal conservative — would favor deficits in 2008-2009 but NOT during expansion
- On fiscal stimulus vs. austerity debate: Both sides can be coherent and rational, but often expressed irrationally
- **Key mistake**: Assuming there's always a good answer when there may not be one

> "The Onion captured the situation perfectly. Their headline after Obama was elected was, 'Black Man Given Nation's Worst Job.'"

- Political solutions must embrace the fact that **US is not as rich as Americans think**
- Difficult choices are unavoidable

### First Job: The Soros ERM Trade (1992)

- First job: Junior trader at **Citigroup** foreign exchange department
- Started the week the **pound was kicked out of the ERM** (Exchange Rate Mechanism)

**George Soros "broke the Bank of England" story**:
- Soros read that Bank of England had £10 billion in reserves to defend the pound
- Soros: "£10 billion. What a remarkable coincidence! That's exactly the size of the position I was thinking of taking."
- O'Shea argued to his boss that UK wouldn't leave ERM because it would be political suicide for conservatives
- Boss smiled and said "Okay, we'll see" — three hours later, pound crashed out

> "I had absolutely no comprehension of the power of markets versus politics. The policy makers didn't understand that either."

- **Lesson**: Policy makers don't understand they're not in control — neither are speculators, but **fundamentals actually matter**
- UK remaining in ERM was untenable: recession with overvalued currency while Germany needed high rates due to reunification inflation
- Soros simply recognized the situation was untenable — like trying to fight gravity

### Trading Philosophy: Markets vs. Policy

> "Markets matter more than policy. You have to look at real fundamentals, not at what policy makers want to happen."

- Willing disbelief can persist, but eventually market overwhelms it
- Soros's genius: Recognizing turning points when things change AND having big risk on the trade when it was right **now**

### The 2006-2007 Bubble: Seeing What No One Cared About

**Pre-crisis bubble indicators (2006-2007)**:
- Risk premiums too low everywhere
- Credit trading at ludicrous spreads with no concern for quality
- Companies posting smooth earnings every quarter = manipulating numbers
- True facts being obscured throughout the system

> "The problem was most obvious in the credit markets. But you can't be short because you lose carry [interest rate payments on the credit instrument], and at the same time, the spreads get lower and lower."

- Being short credit in 2006-2007 was like being short Nasdaq in 1999 — have to wait for the right time

**Bubble positioning strategy**:
- Participated in bubble but kept positions highly liquid with exits
- Did many trades through **options** — bought calls in carry currencies
- **Carry currencies**: Higher interest rate currencies (e.g., Australian dollar at 5% vs. US 1%)
- By being long options: If bubble continues, make returns; if collapses, only lose premium
- Structural reason: Option prices were too cheap due to very low risk premiums

**Federal Reserve rate hike trades**:
- Fed hiking cycle 2005-2006 — futures market kept pricing imminent stops
- Market kept paying to take trades betting Fed wouldn't stop
- Despite obvious bubble signals, monetary policy was still accommodative
- **Great risk/reward trade**: In six months they'll still be hiking
- Kept repeating the trade as months rolled on and market kept saying "I'm sure they'll stop soon"

### Understanding Market Inefficiency

> "I try to avoid conceptualizing the market in anthropomorphic terms. Markets don't think. Just like mobs don't think."

- **Why wasn't the market priced efficiently?** Very few market forces in macro markets compared to real money
- In FX or Treasuries, hedge funds are tiny compared to PIMCO or Chinese government
- "I am a small fish swimming in a sea of real money. Fundamentals matter. I am not playing a game against people like me."

**LTCM example** (Long Term Capital Management):
- Most famous hedge fund failure in history (distinguished from Madoff's Ponzi scheme)
- First four years: steady profits, quadrupled assets
- May-September 1998: Lost all value, plunging 92%
- Enormously leveraged, creating systemic risk to banks and brokerages
- Federal Reserve orchestrated bailout (but didn't pay for it)
- Impressive roster including two Nobel Prize winners
- Before crisis began, O'Shea didn't even know who LTCM was — was prop trading with no contacts

> "Invest first; investigate later." — George Soros quote

- Don't get fixated on needing a story for every trade
- **Empiricist at heart**: "The unfolding reality trumps everything"

### The 1998 Crisis: Trading Without Knowing Why

- T-bond futures going up limit every day signaled something happening
- Didn't need to know why to trade — once reality is happening, trade accordingly
- **Hypothesis testing approach**: Something big is happening, powerful enough to persist, do it in liquid positions
- If wrong, limited loss; if right, unknown upside potential

### 2008 Financial Crisis: When It Really Started

**Timeline debate**:
- Housing prices began declining 2006 — but no market response
- Subprime credit indexes started falling January 2007
- July 2007: Broad credit selloff, but considered "contained"
- Equity people trace start to Bear Stearns collapse (March 2008)

**O'Shea's view**: True start was **August 2007**
- Money markets stopped working — banks didn't trust other banks
- **LIBOR rates spiked** — clearest signal underlying assumptions broken
- Money market desks reported liquidity had dried up completely
- This happened in the most important market (money market = heart of capitalism) but was largely ignored

### August 2007: Turning Bearish

> "Declining housing prices were the impending storm clouds, but it started raining when money markets stopped working."

- Most people didn't notice money markets breaking down
- S&P actually made new highs in next two months

**Critical insight**: Great trades don't require predictions
- Soros's 1992 pound trade based on something that had already happened (deep recession making ERM untenable)
- Late 2007: Clear financial system was imploding, but most participants hadn't noticed

> "Fundamentals are not about forecasting the weather for tomorrow, but rather noticing that it is raining today."

### Why Timing Is So Uncertain in Macro

- **Problem**: As long as no one cares, there is no trend
- Can't be short Nasdaq in 1999 just because fundamentally overpriced
- **Solution**: Wait until people start to care — sell market on way down, not on way up

**2006-2007 market perception**:
- Financial crisis another example of waiting for right time
- During bubble: "It was ridiculous. You saw insanity everywhere."
- Market in completely unsustainable bubble but timing uncertain

> "Taking Nasdaq as an example, you want to be selling Nasdaq at 4,000, but only after it has gone to 5,000."

- In a bubble, who's to say how far it can go?
- Need to wait for and recognize the right time
- Not about being brilliant economist — read the *Financial Times*, recognize when something matters

### Managing Through the Crisis

**Q2 2008 market rebound**:
- Reason: People felt Bear Stearns bailout (March 2008) solved the problem

**O'Shea's view**: **Clearly wrong** — people confused liquidity with solvency
- Bear Stearns and banking system were solvent, they thought
- Thought it was liquidity crisis, just matter of confidence
- **Reality**: Banking system had solvency problem BECAUSE it had liquidity problem
- "You can't fix a solvency problem by adding more liquidity"
- Example: House worth $100K with $10K mortgage — lending another $100K doesn't solve underlying problem, just adds debt
- As housing prices kept falling, solvency problem worsened
- Market behaving as if no problem

**Adjusting positions in Q2 2008**:
- Found better risk/reward trades to express bearish view
- Had been very negative on credit early in year
- By Q2, corporate/bank credit spreads had widened sharply
- In forward market, TED spread priced to narrow dramatically over coming months

**TED spread**: Difference between 3-month LIBOR (bank lending rate) and 3-month T-bill rate
- LIBOR always higher than T-bills (small counterparty risk in interbank loans vs. risk-free Treasuries)
- Normal times: ~25 basis points
- **TED spread widens during "flight-to-quality"** when counterparty/liquidity concerns heighten
- August 2007 freeze: Widened to 200+ basis points
- Post-Lehman 2008: Record 485 basis points
- Wide TED spread often occurs during steep equity declines — **long TED spread is a bearish position**

**Trade rotation**:
- Corporate/bank credit spreads priced to stay wide in forward market
- Rotated out of short credit trades into TED spreads — much better risk/reward
- Q2 2008: Both corporate credit and TED spreads narrowed
- TED priced to narrow in forward market, so trade near breakeven
- If stayed with short corporate credit during Q2 optimism, would have lost significant money
- Switched trade didn't have much downside, so when everybody got optimistic again, bearish position didn't change much

### Post-Lehman Collapse (Late 2008)

**Lehman bankruptcy**:
- If started with premise of solvency issue, everything straightforward
- Banking system underwater — no reason to lend unless government steps in with capital
- Politics in Washington against more bailouts
- Treasury Secretary Paulson made clear: No government bailout of Lehman
- Once Lehman has negative value and no rescue, bankruptcy inevitable

> "Most people knew it was going to happen, but they failed to understand what it meant."

**Crisis management during collapse**:
- Main priority: Make business as safe as possible
- Avoided counterparty exposure to Lehman
- Simplified the book, reduced leverage significantly in 2008
- Restricted trading to highly liquid positions
- Avoided OTC trades with many counterparties
- Confined counterparty risk to strongest counterparties only

**Trades during collapse**:
- Similar to early 2008: Long volatility, short credit, long TED spread, long dollar
- Expected flight to quality
- Common theme: "All the-world-is-going-to-get-scary trades"

### Transition to Recovery (April 2009)

- Stayed with bearish positions through entire decline until started losing money
- **April 2009**: Two things changed
  1. Economy stopped getting worse
  2. Markets started going up
- Underlying problems hadn't gone away, but not the market driver

> "Never underestimate the ability of people to be optimistic and believe that everything is going to be okay."

- What matters to markets: Not whether growth is good/bad, but whether it's getting better or worse
- Growth getting less negative = good news
- Asia, Australian dollar, S&P turning higher by March 2009
- By March-April: Seeing broad-based recovery in global markets

**New trades**:
- Bullish strategies
- Interest rates pricing in Great Depression — once outlook improved slightly, yields could rise significantly
- Went short long-term Treasuries (outright and yield curve play)
- Went short dollar (reversal of flight-to-quality trade)
- Typically 10-15 different trades in portfolio at any time

### Implementation Over Narrative

> "Implementation is the key in everything. Implementation is more important than the trade idea behind it."

- Having beautiful idea doesn't help if implementation wrong
- Tried to implement trades so timing didn't have to be perfect

**Storytelling vs. Reality**:
- Macro most misunderstood when seen as storytelling
- Storytelling is nice way to talk about it, but only 10% of what's important
- **Other 90%**: Implementation and flexibility

**George Soros's key trait**: Least regret of anyone — no emotional attachment to ideas
- Will play up to public image as guru, but in trading has no attachment
- When trade is wrong, just cuts it, moves on, does something else
- Example: Made $250M on huge FX position in one day, quoted in press about strategic view
  - Then market moved against him and position disappeared — didn't let structural views interfere with trading

> "The danger in the narrative I have been giving you is that it may lead to the false impression that what you need to do to make lots of money is be really smart in economics and understand fundamentally what is going on. I don't really believe that is true."

### Empiricism and Flexibility

**What O'Shea actually believes**:
- Need method that suits your personality
- Flexible enough to change mind
- Recognize world as found and adjust

**April 2009 example**:
- Was really pessimistic, thought world in terrible condition
- Market telling him he was wrong
- "Okay, I'm completely wrong. What is a different hypothesis of what is going on?"
- Constructed new hypothesis that fit better
- Explanatory story comes AFTER hypothesis proven wrong

### Macro Process: Empiricism → Theme → Implementation

1. **Empiricism comes first**: Notice what's actually happening
2. **Macro theme to fit observations**: Not grand theory, but testable hypothesis
3. **Implementation of trades**: Must be testable empirically in market

**Difference from trend following**:
- Requires logical fundamental linkages for price movements
- Example: China turning around, metal prices higher, Australian dollar moving up = recovery somewhere in world
- Demand somewhere, S&P may still fall but divergence in data
- Fit: The-whole-world-is-terrible thesis doesn't work anymore
- New hypothesis: Asia-led economic recovery

**Timing advantage**:
- Anticipates future trends rather than waiting for trends to develop then jumping on
- May end up in same trades as trend follower but timing very different

### Equity Trading: Why O'Shea Avoids It

- Trades equity indexes and baskets, but not much
- **Preference**: Interest rate markets or FX are better ways to express trades
- Equity stories make no sense to him
- Reasons trades worked usually nothing like reasons equity people think they worked
- **In entire life**: Only done one single-stock trade — bought Berkshire in 1999

**Berkshire 1999 trade**:
- Price had halved because Buffett refused involvement in dot-com bubble
- O'Shea thought it was stupidest reason ever heard for stock price to halve
- Nasdaq going through roof, Buffett (all-time legend) saying he doesn't understand the stuff, price gets hammered because "dinosaur not part of new paradigm"
- Held until started hedge fund — believed in himself more than Warren Buffett


