## Chapter 5: Jaffray Woodriff - The Third Way

### Overview: Pattern Recognition vs. Trend-Following

**Three trader categories:**
1. **Trend-following CTAs** - seek trends, take position until liquidation/reversal signal
2. **Countertrend/mean reversion CTAs** - take positions opposite to ongoing trend when algorithms signal overextension
3. **Pattern-recognition approaches** - identify patterns suggesting greater probability for higher or lower prices near term

**Woodriff**: among small minority of CTAs using pattern-recognition approach with **unique methodology**
- One of most successful practitioners of systematic trading of any kind

### Background: Working Farm Childhood

- Grew up on **working farm near Charlottesville, Virginia**
- Childhood experiences colored perceptions of work
- High school observation: most people loved Fridays, hated Mondays
- **Goal**: "Make Mondays as exciting as Fridays"

### Grape Harvest Lesson on Incentives

**Summer job**: harvesting grapes in uncle's vineyard with sister
- Initially worked alongside local workers
- Paid by quantity harvested
- **Amazed other employees worked slowly and wasted time**
- Despite same incentive structure, **Woodriff and sister earned 2-3x as much per hour**

**Impact on business philosophy:**
- Clearly understood incentives
- High regard for fairness and efficacy of incentive-based payment
- Firm's unusual incentive structure: **0% management fee, 30% incentive fee** (vs. typical 1-2% management + 20-25% incentive)

### Early Career Path

- Attended **University of Virginia** (20 miles from family farm)
- Knew wanted to be trader before college graduation
- Mother's consternation: after 1991 graduation, **never sought job** - continued developing futures trading systems

**First CTA partnership (pre-graduation):**
- Formed with classmate shortly before graduation
- Lasted only few months
- Partner's family put up seed money = owned 65% of CTA
- **Woodriff amenable to minority share**, but partner thought was Woodriff's boss
- Unacceptable arrangement → quick departure

### Blue Ridge Trading Partnership

**Second CTA: Blue Ridge Trading (1991)**
- **Woodriff**: trading
- **Robert Jordan**: business and marketing
- Hardly immediate success

**Performance:**
- **October 1991 start**: first 3 months + subsequent 2 full years ended slightly below breakeven overall
- **Third year (1994)**: Woodriff's systems generated **80%+ return for first 6 months**

**Partnership dissolution:**
- Never signed partnership agreement
- Split small net earnings until systems became profitable
- With significant profits, Woodriff wanted to formalize with written agreement
- **Terms proposed angered Jordan** → broke off partnership, filed lawsuit
- Blue Ridge relationship ended shortly after
- Firm closed few months later

### Woodriff Trading Launch (1994)

**August 1994 start:**
- Less than $50,000 raised from family
- **Final 5 months 1994**: -16% loss
- **1995**: additional -12% loss
- Very inauspicious beginning followed by **spectacular 180% gain in 1996**

**Performance streak continued:**
<!-- pp. 121-140 -->

## Colm O'Shea (continued)

### QIM Performance Track Record

- **Futures program** (Oct 2003-2011): 12.5% annual return, 10.5% standard deviation, 1.43 Gain to Pain ratio
- **Proprietary futures account** (Dec 2001 start, higher leverage): 118% annual return, 81% standard deviation, 1.94 GPR
- **Equity program** (proprietary, Apr 2000-Sep 2005): 115% annual return, 69% standard deviation, 2.69 GPR
- **Equity program** (client accounts, May 2008 start): 34% annual return, 20% standard deviation, 2.38 GPR
- Zero staff turnover since inception (31 employees)
- Futures program accounts for ~85% of nearly $5 billion AUM

### Early Interests: Probability and Computing

- **Age 9-10**: Obsessed with rolling dice — fascinated by randomness and certainty (seven always beat six and eight)
- **Age 12**: Convinced parents to buy $300 Commodore computer on condition he return it within 30-day guarantee
  - Taught himself programming to simulate dice rolling
  - Skipped school using thermometer trick to get more computer time
  - "Really glad I got to do 30 days of programming back then. Good thing for my evolving brain to experience"

### First Market Experience: The Losing Broker Trade

- Age 18: Family trust account — noticed options moved more than stocks (percentage terms)
- Broker recommended a trade ("It's a layup") — lost money
- **Key lesson**: "One trade; I will never do it again" — never followed another broker recommendation his entire life
- Inspired him to figure out how to predict market direction himself

### October 1987 Crash: Contrarian Instinct

- Day of crash: watching tech stock recommended by family friend (had run from $20 to $40)
- Morning of Oct 20th: stock fell into low teens after crash
- Called Schwab 50+ times to get through busy signals — wanted to **buy** when everyone was selling
- Schwab operator thought he meant "sell" because "No one is buying!"
- Trade filled at $14.50, rallied sharply after
- **Contrarian nature evident from beginning**: "willing to be a contrarian even at the very beginning"

### Early Option Trading: Put/Call Ratio

- Used put/call ratio as primary indicator
- Also watched ARMS Index
- First 10 trades: all put purchases made money (down market 1987)
- Had also been buying calls (most lost money)
- **Memory distortion**: Initially remembered first 10 trades all profitable — actually first 10 **put** trades were profitable
- Account grew from $2,500 to over $10,000
- **11th put trade**: Lost more than all previous gains combined (market rallied sharply, puts expired worthless)

### Position Sizing Disaster

> "Because I kept on increasing my trade size as I made money."

- Blew entire account on one trade by scaling up position size with winnings
- Continued trading after, but unsuccessfully
- Tried daytrading with real-time quote setup — realized after three days:

> "This isn't me. This just doesn't work for me."

### College Trading Contest: Double Entry Strategy

- Junior year: AT&T investment challenge ($50 entry fee)
- Entered under own name AND roommate Will's name (second entry to increase odds)
- Traded two accounts differently
- Came in 6th place on Will's entry — prize was $3,000 cash + Bahamas trip for two
- Will had to accept prize at ceremony (check "about this big" — Woodriff gestures)
- Mock check looked official; tried to cash it at bank (wouldn't fit through teller window)
- Contest organizers encouraged multiple entries and different strategies

### Career Direction: Incentive Fee Structure

- Quickly ruled out broker (commissions) or money manager (management fees only)
- **Incentive fee structure appealed**: pay directly linked to performance
- Attracted to having edge in markets but knew it might not be possible
- Knew some people were beating markets thanks to first *Market Wizards* book

### Economics Course: Rejecting EMH

- Took economics course — horrified by efficient market hypothesis
- Refused to learn material because "I thought a lot of it was wrong"
- Pleaded for essay questions instead of multiple-choice on final exam
- Professor gave multiple-choice anyway
- **Exam strategy**: Took crayons to exam, sat up front where everyone could see
- Wrote note explaining: answering with what he thought were right answers, but for questions where professor wanted different answers, would explain why professor was wrong in separate column
- Professor ignored everything and gave failing grade of 51
- **Woodriff's reaction**: "I don't really care that much about getting a 51—in fact I'm glad I did—because I know how wrong some of the 'correct' answers were"

### Self-Taught Trader

- No mentors in trading methodology
- Self-taught approach after extensive consideration
- **Role model for personality**: **Paul Tudor Jones** — interested in being discretionary trader
- Attended Jones talk at Darden (UVA business school) around time of reading *Market Wizards* (Jones wasn't famous yet)
- Remembered Jones's confidence and charisma

### System Development: University Computer Lab

- After graduation: no personal computer, used UVA engineering school lab
- Huge room with extremely high ceilings, 100+ computers
- Started with trend-following models but found successful trend followers already existed
- Didn't want to compete — wanted something different
- **Breakthrough moment in computer lab**:

> "Right then. Right in that computer lab."

### Discovery of Trend-Neutral Models

- Realized could build **third class of models**: trend neutral on average
- Neither trend following nor countertrend
- Built couple models, did preliminary tests — "a lot of edge in this type of approach"
- Excited to do extensive testing — working on two computers
- Lab got crowded, had to give up one computer
- **Decision**: "This place is going to empty out sometime tonight" — waited until night to use many computers simultaneously
- Worked all night, continued through next day
- Pulled second all-nighter (nearly 40 hours straight on Pepsi/caffeine)
- Dangerous drive home second morning — almost fell asleep at wheel
- Got home, took 3 minutes to tell father what accomplished, slept 24 hours straight
- "When I woke up, I felt completely refreshed"
- Later read "you can't catch up on your sleep" — **"Not true!"**

### Multiple Models Better Than Single Best Model

- Key discovery: **much better to use multiple models than single best model**
- Conversation with mother: "I know you are really frustrated that I didn't interview for jobs after graduating college... if I am successful in what I am working on right now, I will do very well with it. I don't want you to think that I'm doing this just to make money. The really great thing about what I'm doing now is that if I am that good at applying predictive modeling, I will be able to generalize the same approach into science. So I won't just be a trader, even if I am very successful at it."

### The Quantitative Foundation

- Set up foundation to improve statistical prediction methodologies/software
- Prefers terms **"statistical prediction"** or **"statistical learning"** to **"data mining"** (negative connotation from misuse)
- Started with $50 million, now ~$100 million
- Must give away specified percentage yearly (given to schools and local charities)
- **Long-term goal**: Develop generalized software for scientific applications
  - Timeline: possibly 5+ years from full engagement
  - Not grappling with this now because still profiting from edge in markets
  - Plan: If QIM closes after poor performance stretch, would validate techniques by showing edge existed for many years before others caught up
  - Then appropriate time to offer predictive software for general scientific use
- "Building a war chest to do that eventually"

### Early Performance Turnaround (1993-1994)

- **First 3 months + 2 full years at Blue Ridge**: down slightly
- **Next 6 months**: up over 80%
- Stark performance contrast suggests major methodology change

#### Two Critical Changes (1993):

**1. Market-specific models → Common models across all markets**
- Market-specific models more vulnerable to overfitting (curve-fitting to past data)
- Found: more data used to train models, better the performance
- Same models across multiple markets = far more robust approach
- **Big change**: moving from separate models per market to common models across all markets

**2. Increased diversification**
- Started trading only 2 markets, then 3 markets
- Cherry-picking markets that looked best in backtesting (rookie curve-fitting error)
- As AUM increased, added substantially more markets
- Transition to greater diversification helped performance
- **By 1994**: trading ~20 markets, no longer using market-specific models

### System Concepts: Neither Trend Following Nor Mean Reversion

- **Trend-neutral models**: neither trying to project continuation nor reversal of trend
- Only trying to predict probable market direction over next 24 hours
- Over 1,000 models in system

### Bill James Influence: Secondary Variables

> "Baseball Abstract cover to cover each year. He was creating and quantifying new and interesting statistics."

- **Bill James's approach**: Created statistics more informative and predictive than traditional stats
  - Example: 21-year-old hitting .311 more interesting than 26-year-old hitting same
  - James did normalizations (adjusting for batting slot, etc.)
  - "I loved the logic of normalizing data"
- **Connection to trading**: James's quantitative analysis style influenced how Woodriff built trading systems
- Over past 10 years, James's analytical style recognized and deployed by baseball establishment

### Secondary Variables from Price Data

- **James's method**: Creative measures from basic data → more informative statistics
- **Woodriff's method**: Price data → secondary variables (quantifications derived from price with no direct relationship to price direction)
- Example secondary variable: **volatility measure** (derived from price, but no direct relationship to price direction)
- Idea for secondary variables came from Bill James
- All secondary variables derived **only from daily open, high, low, close**
- Does NOT use GNP or other economic variables (tried, couldn't get it to work)
- Combined different secondary variables into trend-neutral models

### System Discovery Process: Data Mining Done Right

**Conventional approach** (hypothesis-driven):
- Start with valid hypothesis based on structural theory/qualitative understanding
- Test hypothesis to see if supported by data

**Woodriff's approach** (data-driven):
> "I don't do that. I read all of that just to get to the point that I do what I am not supposed to do, which is a really interesting observation because I am supposed to fail."

- Reads David Shaw interview from *Stock Market Wizards*
- Shaw quote on pattern testing:

> "The more variables you have, the greater the number of statistical artifacts that you're likely to find, and the more difficult it will generally be to tell whether a pattern you identify actually has any predictive value. We take great care to avoid methodological pitfalls associated with 'overfitting the data'... Rather than blindly searching through the data for patterns—an approach whose methodological dangers are widely appreciated within, for example, the natural science and medical research communities—we typically start by formulating a hypothesis based on some sort of structural theory or qualitative understanding of the market, and then test that hypothesis to see if it is supported by the data."

**Woodriff's rebuttal**:
- "According to almost everyone, you have to approach systematic trading (and predictive modeling in general) from the framework of 'Here is a valid hypothesis that makes sense within the context of the markets.' Instead, I blindly search through the data."
- Wants to be able to search unlimited combinations and automate the process
- If cross-validation set up properly, overfitting is problem that can be overcome
- Hypothesized patterns that work exist; would rather have computer test trillions of patterns than few hundred thought of manually
- **One manual aspect**: List of secondary variables derived from price must make sense (e.g., volatility, price acceleration might provide important information)
- Then framework combines secondary variables in all combinations to see what works

### Avoiding Data Mining Pitfalls

**Problem with commercial software** (SAS, IBM):
- Focused on allowing users to handle large quantities of data
- NOT focused on providing strict protocols to avoid curve-fitting
- Users excited about building models with more data than ever before — missing point of doing process properly
- Software fails to guide users AND leads them in wrong direction (allows generating bogus evidence to support pet theories)

#### Proper Methodology to Avoid Overfitting

**Training vs. Validation**:
- Use data up to a year before current date as **training data set**
- Final year data as **validation data set**
- Ongoing real-time data as **test** (track record becomes test data set)

**Random data baseline test**:
- Generate random numbers with same distribution characteristics as target variable (price change over next 24 hours)
- Any models scoring well on this intentionally bogus data are 100% curve-fitted
- Performance of best model on fictitious data = **baseline**
- Need models that do much better than this baseline when training on real data
- Only performance **difference** between real data models and baseline is indicative of expected performance

**Avoiding cherry-picking**:
- Use in-sample data for training, out-of-sample for testing
- Common error: Sort models by in-sample performance, choose best ones to test on out-of-sample
- This turns out-of-sample into part of training data (cherry-picks models that did best in out-of-sample period)
- **Correct approach**: Look for patterns where **on average** all models out-of-sample continue to do well
- Generally good if out-of-sample results are 50%+ of in-sample score
- QIM's business model would never have worked if SAS/IBM were building great predictive modeling software

### Historical Data Value

- Sometimes give slightly more weight to recent data
- **Old data still highly valuable**: "stationarity of the patterns we have uncovered is amazing"
- Would have expected predictive patterns to change more over longer term
- Implication: models don't get dropped even if they perform poorly
- "tremendous amount of deterioration" required to drop a model
- Current year performance of any single model not predictive of next year's performance
- **What is predictive**: how model performed over entire 31 years
- Extra 3% of data from most recent year doesn't make much difference in how model performed over entire training period

### Capacity and Scalability

**Current capacity**: $6-9 billion (futures program alone at ~$5 billion AUM)
- Capacity not static — moves with changes in volume and volatility
- If volatilities decline 50% on average, capacity reduced by similar amount

**Changes to expand capacity**:
1. Execute trades throughout trading session (not just on opening)
2. Shifted allocation to give greater weight to more liquid markets
   - Trade larger percentage in stock indexes and interest rates
   - Smaller percentage in nonfinancial futures
   - Reduced diversification but strong pattern for edge to be greater in more liquid markets
   - Allocation shift improved performance besides increasing capacity

**Risk weighting by liquidity**:
- Started shifting weightings to more liquid markets in 2006
- ~6 months ago: switched risk weightings to be exclusively based on liquidity
- One exception: S&P (substantial excess capacity)

### Risk Management

**Core technique**: Exponentially weighted moving average of daily dollar range per contract
- Kept volatility relatively stable near target level despite wide gyrations in markets
- Particularly proud: Through chaos of 2008-2009, volatility remained very near target of 12% annualized

**Volatility adjustment**:
- As volatility increased, number of contracts traded dropped precipitously
- Works extremely well for entire history of program

**Leverage reduction policy** (worked poorly 2010-2011):
- Initial formulation: On intramonth drawdown of 6% from monthly equity peak, cut exposure to 75% of normal
- 8% drawdown → 50% exposure
- 10% drawdown → 25% exposure
- Analogous rules for increasing exposure back up as drawdown reduced
- **2003-2009**: Leverage reduction rule slightly lowered return/risk but made it easier to sleep (trading size smaller in significant drawdowns)
- **2010-2011**: Policy hurt badly — models really on fire when exposure was lowest
- Borrowing term from trend following: "whipsawed by our own risk overlay"

**Dilemma of drawdown risk reduction**:
- If mean reversion applies to systematic trading performance, then system not working well for period → greater probability it will do well in subsequent period
- Reducing risk after drawdown = smallest exposure exactly when you would have smallest exposure
- **But**: Reducing exposure after losses mitigates chances of catastrophic loss
- Woodriff: "Both perspectives are true—reducing exposure after losses will mitigate the chances of a catastrophic loss, but it will do so at the cost of adversely impacting performance"

### Market Misconceptions

**Worst misconception**: What should constitute "free market"
- OTC markets continue to grow unbounded as massive profit center for Wall Street banks
- Allowing OTC markets to be unregulated and opaque "makes as much sense as leaving 50 eight-year-olds unsupervised for a month"
- OTC markets used to take advantage of "sophisticated" clients who are naive in practice
- **OTC markets**: built to maximize asymmetries of information
- Example of how markets should NOT operate
- **Markets should be**: fair and transparent (like futures and equities markets have mostly evolved to be)

### Worst Public Mistakes

- **Overtrading**
- **Listening to tips**

### Handling Losing Periods

- Periods of poor performance are difficult
- Handles it by focusing very hard on improving the trading system

### Trading Rules Summary

1. **Look where others don't** — adjust position sizes to overall risk to target particular volatility
2. **Pay careful attention to transaction costs**

### Final Words

> "When I was in my teens, my highly insightful father was somehow able to instill in me the discipline of objectively evaluating your own progress. That lesson, more than anything else, has been critical to my success."

---

## Key Insights from Woodriff Interview

### Four Important Trading System Insights:

**1. Systems can be neither trend following nor countertrend**
- Third class of models exists that works better than either common approach
- Woodriff's return/risk comparison to universe of systematic traders suggests edge from this approach

**2. Data mining can work if done properly**
- Possible to search huge quantities of data to find useful patterns without curve fitting
- Important caveat: most people will misuse the approach
- Find patterns that worked very well in past but fail in actual trading

**3. Old price data nearly as meaningful as recent data**
- Data 30 years old can be nearly as valuable as recent data

**4. Systems working broadly across markets more robust**
- Systems that work well across many markets more likely to continue working in actual trading
- Design systems that work broadly rather than market-specific systems

### Volatility-Based Position Sizing (Broadly Applicable)

- Adjusting position sizes in line with changing overall volatility applicable to wide range of traders
- Not just for systematic traders
- As markets become more volatile → trade smaller number of contracts for same asset size
- **Woodriff's metric**: Average dollar range in contract value for each market traded
- Using this approach: maintained portfolio volatility close to desired target despite widely fluctuating volatility over 20 years

### Contrarian Personality as Edge

- Developed methodology suited to personality
- Deep inner need to develop approach different from what anyone else was doing
- Able to recognize early when methodology didn't suit him
- After setting up real-time quote system for manual daytrading, abandoned after only 3 days:

> "This isn't me. This just doesn't work for me."

---

**Footnotes:**

¹ **CTAs (Commodity Trading Advisors)**: Managers who trade futures, registered with CFTC. Nomenclature poorly chosen on at least two grounds: (1) CTAs are managers, not advisors, and (2) large majority of trading is in financial markets (stock indexes, interest rates, currencies) rather than commodities.

² Management fees collected on AUM. Incentive fees collected as percent of profits above high-water mark (highest NAV level at which incentive fees previously collected). Almost all CTAs and hedge funds charge both types of fees; Woodriff charges higher-than-normal incentive fee but no management fee.

³ Actual account compounded by lesser amount because Woodriff was withdrawing money to cover living expenses and pay Geismar.

⁴ Woodriff first interview conducted for book and also last chapter completed. Year+ later, sent completed chapter to check accuracy. Email back: "If you can believe it, coming full circle for this chapter, I am coming down with another bad cold right now and my head is fogging up!"

⁵ Data mining: using computers to analyze large amounts of data to discover patterns. Can uncover patterns impossible for humans to find empirically or by prior hypotheses, but can also identify spurious patterns (statistical artifacts with no predictive value).

