### Blackjack Casino Experience (continued)

- First casino trip 1961 (MIT spring break) with **Kimmel** (Mr. X) and **Eddie Hand** (Mr. Y from book)
- Thorp didn't know about their mob connections initially—Hand seemed rough but both were wealthy
- Hand owned trucking business, sold to Ryder; his warrants alone worth $47M during warrant market boom
- Started with $10,000 bankroll, scaled bet sizes gradually: $1-$10 → $2-$20 → $10-$50 → $25-$300 → $50-$500 (max)
- Predicted doubling $10,000 to ~$20,000; actual result $11,000—"extremely close to prediction"

> "Don't bet more than you are comfortable with. Just take your time until you're ready."

**Lesson: managing money stuck with me forever after**

### Transition from Casinos to Markets

- After proving casino games beatable, asked: **"The biggest game in the world is Wall Street. Why don't I look at and learn about that?"**
- Summer 1964: intensive stock market reading—**Barron's** to **Random Character of Stock Prices**
- Most books "helpful in the negative"—e.g., **Technical Analysis** by **Edwards and McGee** convinced him technical analysis was "a road not to go down"
- Discovered **RMH Warrants and Low Price Stock Survey** by **Sydney Fried**—realized warrant pricing should be mathematizable
- Key insight: variables affecting stock prices mostly eliminated when focused on warrants (underlying price, strike, volatility, time to expiration, interest rate)

### Warrant Pricing Formula Development

- Fall 1965: transferred to UC Irvine, met **Sheen Kassouf** who already had theoretical warrant model
- Kassouf making steady money hedging warrant positions
- Collaborated on **Beat the Market** (published strategy)
- **1967**: Thorp developed option-pricing formula assuming risk-free growth rate
- Formula equivalent to future **Black-Scholes formula**—started using it in 1967

**Why publish Beat the Market?**
- Believed similar discoveries inevitable (like **Newton/Leibniz**, **Darwin/Wallace**)
- Writing book would attract investors for money management
- After Black-Scholes published (1972-73), "it was too late. I don't have any regrets"

### Early Warrant Trading

- Theme: warrants <2 years to expiration traded at excessive premiums
- Strategy: short overpriced warrant, hedge by buying stock (**delta hedging**)
- Initially static hedge, then switched to **dynamic delta hedging**
- Split from Kassouf—different views: Kassouf took fundamental views on stocks, Thorp insisted on delta-neutral hedging ("I didn't believe I had any forecasting power")

### First Black-Scholes Application (1967-68)

- Went naked short on most overpriced warrants (lacked capital for full diversified hedged portfolio)
- 1967-68: terrible timing—large bull market (small caps +84% in 1967, +36% in 1968)
- Formula good enough that even naked short positions broke even despite adverse market
- **"First actual application of the Black-Scholes formula in the markets"** (1967-1968)

### Convertible Bond Arbitrage

**Convertible bond definition**: corporate bond convertible into fixed number of shares at specified price—combination of bond + call option

- Lower interest rates than corporate bonds due to embedded option value
- **Convertible arbitrage**: buy convertible bond, short sufficient stock to neutralize long exposure (delta hedging)
- Simple model treated convertible as corporate bond + warrant, assumed bond provides price floor
- Discovered floor assumption wrong: if stock falls enough, bond grade also falls—"price floor was not a floor"
- Built sophisticated model accounting for this, analyzing entire family of related instruments (bonds, options, warrants, convertible preferreds) to find optimal hedge combinations

### Fisher Black Interaction

- After Princeton Newport closed, called **Fisher Black** to sell model to Goldman Sachs
- Black flew out, reviewed 3 days, agreed model "looked very good"
- Problem: coded for Digital Equipment computers—Goldman would need to recode
- Black didn't buy it; 2-3 years later built his own convertible bond model

### Kelly Criterion for Position Sizing

**Formula**: F = P_w - (P_L/W)
- F = fraction of capital to bet
- P_w = probability of winning
- P_L = probability of losing
- W = dollars won per dollar wagered (win size / loss size)

**Key properties**:
- Maximizes compounded growth over long run
- Proportional overbetting more harmful than underbetting
- Betting half Kelly reduces return 25%, betting double Kelly produces negative expected return
- Assumes no minimum bet size; with minimums, ruin is possible

**Thorp learned from Claude Shannon at MIT** (Bell Labs, leading light after Kelly)
- Shannon referenced Kelly's 1956 paper
- Recommended using Kelly for favorable situations betting

**Practical considerations beyond Kelly**:
- Kelly assumes precisely known edge—not true in markets
- Kelly ignores volatility impact beyond returns
- **Real constraint: maximum tolerable drawdown, not zero**
- With $1M bankroll and $200K max drawdown, effective capital is $200K for Kelly purposes

> "I believe that betting half Kelly is psychologically much better... if you bet half the Kelly amount, you get about three-quarters of the return with half the volatility."

**Why bet less than Kelly in trading (vs. blackjack)**:
- Blackjack: probabilities known precisely
- Trading: probability of winning always an estimate
- Uncertainty of probabilities + asymmetry in returns (marginal utility of extra gain < marginal utility of equal % loss)
- Dealer cheating risk in blackjack also warrants scaling back

### AT&T Baby Bells Trade

- Old AT&T exchanged for new AT&T + stock in 7 Baby Bells
- Could buy old AT&T, short new AT&T when issued, lock in ~3/4% spread
- Put on 5 million shares = $330 million position
- Capital base ~$70 million—"largest trade done on NYSE up to that point"
- Size: "all we could get"—appeared nearly risk-free but "there are no zero-risk trades"

### Statistical Arbitrage Development

**Indicators Project (1979)**:
- Searched for indicators with forecasting power: earnings surprises, dividend payout rates, book-to-price
- ~30-40 indicators investigated
- **MUD strategy** (most up, most down): buy diversified portfolio of most-down stocks, short most-up stocks
- Most-up stocks tended to underperform; most-down tended to outperform
- Colleague **William F. Donoghue** quipped: "Thorp, my advice is to buy low and sell high"

**Returns and risk**:
- ~20% annual return before costs
- High risk—two sides didn't track closely
- Issues: reduce risk, reduce transaction costs
- Felt viable as part of larger portfolio

**Dividend/earnings patterns**:
- No-dividend stocks: above-normal returns
- Low-dividend stocks: below-normal returns
- Returns increased with dividend payout (U-shaped curve)
- Earnings surprises had impact for considerable time (weeks/months)—market slow to assimilate

### Gerry Bamberger and Industry Neutrality

- 1985: placed Wall Street Journal ad seeking "reliable ideas that would produce provable excess returns"
- **Gerry Bamberger** responded—had discovered statistical arbitrage at Morgan Stanley (~1982)
- Developed around 1982, eventually shouldered aside by **Nunzio Tartaglia**
- Left Morgan Stanley, saw Thorp's ad
- **Key innovation**: grouped stocks by industry, set up long/short portfolios within each industry
- **Industry neutrality significantly reduced risk**

**Character sketch** (from Thorp articles):
> "Tall trim Orthodox Jew with very high I.Q., original way of looking at problems in finance, wry sense of humor. Every day for the last six years: tuna salad sandwich for lunch."

- Heavy smoker—negotiated compromise: step outside to smoke (Thorp's office no-smoking policy)

**Partnership structure**:
- Joint venture Bamberger ran from New York
- Thorp funded it, Bamberger programmed it
- Essentially franchise operation—Bamberger smart, efficient, got own people, ran own shop
- "Well worth paying him to do all this"

### Statistical Arbitrage Evolution

**Initial returns**: couple years of good performance, then decline

**1986 refocus**:
- Applied **factor neutrality** via **principal components analysis**
- Goal: make strategy factor neutral to reduce risk
- **Abstract factor analysis** vs. economic factors analysis:
  - Economic factors: known items (equity index prices, oil prices)
  - Abstract factors: mathematical constructs from return data, perpendicular vectors in data space
  - Abstract factors avoid multicollinearity problem
  - Biggest abstract factor = stock market

**Implementation**:
- Applied factor neutrality → returns up, risk way down
- Started researching 1986 as Bamberger's returns declined
- Bamberger left 1987

**Results (1989-2002)**:
- October 1987 crash occurred during gap when not trading—"too bad... missed out on really great returns"
- High 20s returns "pretty consistently" until 1989
- Princeton Newport wound down after Princeton office legal troubles with Giuliani
- **August 1992**: restarted statistical arbitrage (low spot for strategy)
- Performance improved consistently
- ~10 years: 21% annualized return before fees/leverage, 7% standard deviation

**2002 shutdown**:
- Returns declining
- Uncertain if temporary or permanent
- More money chasing same strategy than ever
- Would require constant innovation to stay ahead
- Two key employees wanted larger profit share (unreasonably large)

> "Life is getting shorter; it is time to do some other things."

**Retrospective check**: few years ago running ~8% annualized—"not good enough to make me want to go back"

### David Shaw

- 1988: Shaw left Solomon, seeking statistical arbitrage startup funding
- Met Thorp, talked 6 hours
- Strategy redundant with Thorp's—parted on friendly terms

