## Edward Thorp (continued)

### Hedge Fund Investing and Due Diligence

- **Hedge fund edge diminishing**: Still exists but "not by very much" compared to earlier years
- **Current hedge fund investments**: Number diminishing as funds prove less good than expected or returns decline
- **Fund screening criteria**: Eliminated funds with annualized standard deviation >15%, returns <12%, or any bad year

### Bruce Kovner and Intuitive Trading

- **Kovner's qualitative approach**: "Good qualitative grasp of all kinds of interconnections in the markets"
- **Oil tanker investment (Empress Des Mers)**: Bought 20 feet of the world's largest tanker with Kovner
  - Purchased just above scrap value during tanker surplus
  - Older tankers in mothballs, scrap value ~$4M
  - Functioned as option on oil market
  - When oil activity increased, tanker demand surged and generated substantial profits
  - Eventually sold for scrap years later

### Warren Buffett Connection

- **First meeting (1968)**: Through **Ralph Gerard**, dean of graduate school and Buffett investor
- Gerard introduced Thorp to Buffett when Buffett Partnership Ltd. was closing (Buffett thought stocks at crazy heights in 1968)
- **Early assessment**: "Really smart person... thought he would be the richest person in the U.S. someday"
- **Berkshire Hathaway purchase (1982)**: Lost track of Buffett, then learned Berkshire became his private mutual fund
- Shares sold at $12 in 1964, Thorp bought at $985 in 1982

### Trend Following Evolution

- **Initial skepticism**: "Ten years ago, I wouldn't have believed it" — changed mind after research
- **Trend following research**: Began 2006, launched trading program late 2007
- **Program performance**: "Reasonably well" but not as compelling as Princeton Newport or statistical arbitrage
- **Sharpe ratio**: "Little better than 1.0 annualized"
- **Program shutdown (2010)**: Wife diagnosed with brain cancer — "Life is too short"
- **Better than most trend-following programs** managing significant money

### Enhanced Trend Following Methodology

- **Technical + fundamental combination**: Key differentiator from vanilla trend following
- **Fundamental factors varied by sector**:
  - Metals/agriculture: Spread structure (backwardation/contango), storage capacity
  - Currencies: Factors irrelevant
- **Market-specific fundamental filters** defining favorable/unfavorable environments
- **Risk reduction approaches**:
  - Correlation matrix tracked (60-day lookback optimal balance)
  - Reduced exposure in correlated markets when system signaled same direction
  - Smaller positions when high correlation and system wanted long both or short both
- **Portfolio insurance-like process**: Lost 5% → shrink positions; another few percent → shrink more
  - Gradual shutdown as drawdown deepened, then earn way out
  - Wait for 5-10% drawdown threshold before reducing positions
  - Incremental 1% position reduction with each additional 1% drawdown
- **Maximum drawdown**: 14-15%, trading only ~1/3 of normal base position size
- **At 20% drawdown**: Position reduced to zero, wouldn't restart ("system not as good as thought")

### Edge Confidence and Risk Management Philosophy

- **High conviction strategies**: "If you have a really strong conviction about your edge, then the best thing to do is sit there and take your lumps"
- **Uncertain edge strategies**: "If you believe there is a reasonable chance that you might not have an edge, then you better have a safety mechanism"
- **Trend following uncertainty**: Could never be sure of edge, wanted safety mechanism
- **Convertible arbitrage contrast**: High confidence in payoff probabilities, so reducing exposure on drawdowns unnecessary
- **Kelly criterion in trend following**: Bet size such small fraction of Kelly "it didn't make any difference"
- Estimated equivalent to **1/10 or 1/20 of Kelly**

### Madoff Investigation (1991)

- **Initial contact**: Major institutional investor in Princeton Newport asked review of allocation process for pension fund
- **Manager examined**: One hedge fund manager "remarkable" — printed positive returns of 1-2% virtually every month for several years
- **Fraud conclusion reached quickly**: "Very quickly determined that the manager was a fraud"

#### Analysis Process

- **Claimed strategy**: Buy stock, buy put slightly below stock price, sell call slightly above stock price
- Premium received for call approximately balanced premium paid for put
- **Strategy problem**: Protected from loss in any given month, but **"certainly didn't mean that he would win every month"**
- Strong upmarket: Would profit (difference between call strike and stock purchase price)
- Significant down month: Would lose (puts exercised at lower prices than stock purchase)
- **Expected outcome**: Some very good months, some very bad months, diversification across stocks
- **Actual returns**: Not consistent with claimed strategy given market conditions

#### Red Flags in Statements

- **Miraculous trades**: Periodically appeared to eliminate potential losing months and reduce big winning months to moderate winners
- **S&P futures positions**: Long or short, timed to arrive in right month and right amount "to smooth everything out"
- **Trade confirmations**: Received in bundles every few weeks
- **Accountant**: Friend of Madoff, ran one-man shop, been Madoff's accountant since 1960s
- **Information technology**: Brother Peter Madoff in charge
- **Access denied**: "There is no way I will let him in the front door" — Peter wouldn't give reason

#### Detailed Forensic Analysis

- Brought boxes of confirmations and statements back to California
- **Individual trade analysis**: Most trades could never have been made
  - Stock trades too difficult to prove false
  - **Half of option trades**: Options didn't even trade on transaction date — zero volume
  - About quarter of remaining: Couldn't have traded at prices quoted
  - Remaining quarter: Couldn't determine if trades occurred
- **Brokerage verification**: Took 10 trades to high-placed brokerage friend to check counterparties
  - Madoff's organization didn't appear as counterparty on any trades

#### Recommendation and Outcome

- **Conclusion**: "He is printing fake trades. He is making it all up"
- **Advice**: "Get out as soon as you can and as quietly as you can. This is a huge Ponzi scheme that will get bigger and bigger, and one day it is going to self-destruct"
- **Client response**: They got out
- **Further action considered**: Thought of exposing it, but "already had a belly full of government with Giuliani and Princeton Newport Partners"
- **SEC report consideration**: Previously found small frauds, told by lawyer friend (8 years at SEC) "it would be a waste of time reporting it"
- **SEC attitude**: "They didn't care about stuff like that"

### Efficient Market Hypothesis

- **EMH as hollow claim**: Cannot prove negative (no edge possible), but can disprove if people have demonstrable edge
- **Market inefficiency definition**: Participant who can generate excess risk-adjusted returns logically explained and difficult to rebut
- **Convertible arbitrage as proof**: Can explain exactly how it works, why it works, approximate expected return
- **Daily Princeton Newport success**: Questions weren't "Is the market efficient?" but "How inefficient is the market?" and "How can we exploit the inefficiencies?"

### Market Philosophy Summary

- **Inefficiencies exist**: "There for the finding, but they are fairly hard to find"
- **Finding harder over time**: "Gotten harder for me, but that may only be because I am older and less interested, and have more money, which makes me less motivated"
- **Core advice**: Title of book by ex-sister-in-law — *Do What You Love and the Money Will Follow*
- **Skill application**: Figure out skill set and apply to markets
  - Good at accounting → might be good value investor
  - Strong in computers and math → might do best with quantitative approach

## Chapter Summary: Gambling and Investing Parallels

### Thorp's Unified Approach

- **Gambling and investing similarities**: Both probability-based games where edge problem could be solved analytically
- Standard assumption: No analytical solution existed for either
- **Defied preconceptions in both domains**: Applied same scientific thinking and mathematical reasoning
- **Risk management consistency**: Same principles in gambling pertinent to trading

### Beating Roulette

- **Mathematical impossibility assumption**: Widely believed roulette couldn't be beaten
- **Thorp's approach**: Completely different perspective — focused on predicting most likely termination zone for ball
- **Result**: Created **44% edge**
- **Lesson**: "Sometimes what seems impossible is entirely possible if approached from a completely different perspective"
- **Trading analogy**: Even if markets can't be beaten with conventional approaches, doesn't mean unconventional approaches have same limitation

### Blackjack Innovation

- **Basic system insight**: Improved odds by varying bet size based on probabilistic decisions (when to hit, hold, split, double down)
- **Betting more on high-probability hands** transformed losing game into significant positive edge
- **Trading analogy**: Varying position size can be as important as entry methodology
- Trading smaller (or not at all) for lower probability trades and larger for higher probability trades can transform losing strategy into winning one
- Thorp had to bet on even low-probability blackjack hands; **traders can forgo lower probability trades altogether**

### Probability Assessment in Trading

- **Blackjack advantage**: Probabilities can be accurately assessed
- **Trading reality**: Probabilities cannot be accurately assessed
- **Quantitative traders**: Can differentiate via statistical analysis of past results for different strategies
- **Discretionary traders**: Many have strong confidence differences for different trades
- If trader does better on high-confidence trades, **confidence level serves as proxy for probability of winning**
- **Implication**: Trade larger on high-confidence trades, smaller or not at all on low-confidence trades

### Confidence and Risk Management

- **Confidence relevance**: Determines trade size and risk management approach
- **Arbitrage trades (maximum theoretical risk approximated)**: Didn't consider reducing exposure if position went against him
- **Trend following (directional, edge uncertain)**: Made exposure reduction on drawdowns part of methodology
- **Gambling lesson**: "Don't bet more than you are comfortable with. Just take your time until you're ready"
- Drove original blackjack backers crazy: Starting $1 on bad hands, maximum $10 on good hands (ridiculous small wagers given edge)
- **Perspective on risk and comfort level**: Sound advice for traders
- **Emotions deadly for trading**: Surest way to guarantee emotions will impact decisions is trading beyond comfort level

### Market Behavior and Solutions

- **Holy Grail myth**: Many traders mistakenly believe in single solution to defining market behavior
- **Reality**: No single solution, any solutions continually changing
- **Successful traders adapt**: Change approach as dictated by market
- **Finding success = dynamic process**, not static

### Statistical Arbitrage Adaptation

- **Initial concept**: Balance long positions (stocks down most) with short positions (stocks up most) so portfolio net exposure near zero
- **Return/risk deterioration**: Thorp switched to strategy variation adding sector neutrality to market neutrality
- **Sector neutral started losing edge**: Switched to strategy neutralizing portfolio to various factors
- **Third iteration adapted**: Original system version significantly degraded
- **Consistent extreme strong return/risk performance** by adapting and changing strategy
- Staying with original system because it worked so well at one time would have fared poorly

### Kelly Criterion and Trade Sizing

- **Optimal size theoretical answer**: Kelly criterion mathematically yields higher cumulative return over long run than any other strategy
- **The rub**: Kelly assumes probability of winning and ratio of amount won to amount lost per wager are precisely known
- **Games of chance**: Assumption typically true
- **Trading reality**: Probability of winning unknown, at best only estimated (often with wide error)
- **Steep penalty for overestimation**: Overestimating probability of winning (or ratio of average win to average loss) has **negative impact twice as large** as underestimating correct trade size by same amount
- **If precise probabilities unknown**: Bet size should be significantly smaller than full Kelly amount

### Kelly Criterion Volatility Problem

- **Even if correct Kelly known**: Resulting equity stream far too volatile for most people's comfort level
- **High volatility not merely aesthetic**: Important practical implications
- Greater volatility → greater chance trader abandons approach on drawdown
- **Thorp recommendation**: Using **half Kelly** better alternative than full Kelly for most people, even if probability of winning and average win/average loss ratio reasonably estimated
- **Wide error in estimates**: Only very small fraction of Kelly should be risked on any trade
- **Thorp's trend following estimate**: Trade size probably **less than 1/10 of Kelly** (so small didn't even use Kelly criterion to size trades)

### Kelly Criterion Utility Guidelines

- **If you can roughly estimate probability and win/loss ratio**: Kelly criterion very useful in defining appropriate trade size
- Even in this instance, **half Kelly better choice than full Kelly** for most people
- **If probability subject to wide error**: Even half Kelly probably much too large, Kelly criterion of limited use
