## Part Three: EQUITY TRADERS

## Chapter 9: Steve Clark — Do More of What Works and Less of What Doesn't

### Background and Early Career

**Working-class origins**:
- Third generation in same council house (government housing), outskirts of London
- Father absent, half-raised by grandparents
- Left school at **age 17** after doing A levels a year early
- No family university background

**Entry into finance**:
- Friend **Grant** called: "You should come and work in the city. There are 25-year-olds earning £50,000."
- Clark's naive thought: *"Okay, I will go work in the city then and be a trader."* Didn't even know what a trader was.

**First attempts**:
- Worked for hi-fi installation company (designing home stereo layouts, lifting things, driving a van)
- Wrote many places seeking city jobs — always rejected: "no degree, no interview," or "no experience, no interview"

**Manufacturers Hanover backoffice interview**:
- Talked about wanting to be trader with "absolutely no thought to the fact that the fellow interviewing me wanted somebody to work in the backoffice"
- Didn't get job but learned: "The sensible thing to do was to get some experience"
- **1986**: Shortage of backoffice people
- Got temporary filing clerk job, embroidered CV at each temporary position
- Strategy: Say he could do job, figure out how once hired

**Two permanent job offers**:
- **Merrill Lynch**: Run backoffice, £30,000
- **Warburg Securities**: Blue button (trainee on trading floor), £7,000

### Blue Button at Warburg Securities

**Blue button role**:
- Stock exchange floor badge system — color indicated role
- Blue buttons: "boys who were trainees, but who in reality were treated as slaves"
- Chose £7,000 job over £30,000 because it got him on trading floor

**Interview moment**:
- Asked if he gambled
- Clark: "I would never bet on anything where the odds were against me. Why would you do that?"
- Instinctive answer that got him the job

**Initial experience**:
- Started on South African gold shares, gold shares — job: get tea, coffee, sandwiches, answer phone
- "Really had a miserable time on the first desk I was on. I couldn't understand what was going on, and no one was willing to answer a question or teach me anything."
- **Transferred to European desk** — "completely different attitude. They were very happy to talk to me and to teach me."

### October 19, 1987 — First Day Trading

**First week running Scandinavian market-making book** — trader on holiday
- Literally **October 19, 1987** was first day given book to run on his own — the crash

**Monday morning of the crash**:
- Came in long only
- Boss on holiday
- Previous week: Large institutional buy order expected for basket of stocks
- Trader had bought stocks in anticipation, so Clark came in Monday morning long only

**Making prices during crash** (example: **Electrolux**):
- Most vivid memory: Making price on Electrolux
- Gets call asking for price
- Quotes: **43 bid/44 offered**
- Caller offers 10,000 shares at 43 — buys 2,500 shares
- Changes price to **42½ bid/43½ offered**
- Phone rings again — offered 10,000 shares, buys 2,500 at 42½
- Reasoning: "If I drop my price by a full $1 to 41½/42½, and I get hit on the offer, I would be selling my shares at a loss."
- Set price at **42/43**, got hit with offer, bought another 2,500 shares at 42

**Learning moment with German trader**:
- Showed trades to experienced German trader: "I've done these trades; what price should I make now?"
- German looks at him "like I am a complete imbecile"
- Makes price **36/37** and still gets hit with offer at 36
- **Clark had been making totally wrong prices** — had no clue what was going on
- **Key lesson**: "The price is where anyone is prepared to deal, and it can be anything."
- Had one year experience, limited volatility exposure — couldn't comprehend changing price by more than $1, let alone $6 (nearly 15%)

**Systems down scenario**:
- All systems were down during crash
- Clark was determining the price — getting calls asking for prices
- Other market makers present but couldn't see their prices

**German trader's advice**:
- "Your position is growing. You cannot afford to let your next trade be a purchase. Whatever you have to do, you need to make sure that your next trade is a sell."
- Quoted price down by $6 and still ended up buying

**Outcome**:
- Long inventory at start — lost several million pounds that day
- German trader was short everything — made several million pounds

### Rise to Most Profitable Trader

- Smart German hired by Clark years later, also hired trader who ran Scandinavian book (his boss)
- Began trading other books in European area when people on holiday
- Eventually became **most profitable trader in the group**

**What made him profitable**:
- **Very proactive in orientating the book**: "If I was in something that was wrong, I would cut it. I wouldn't defend it. I wouldn't average down. I would just cut it, cut it, cut it."
- **Lack of fear** from inexperience: "I didn't have the fear—the fear that cripples people who have been in the business too long"
- Most traders can't maintain ability to take risk throughout career — "too many bad things happen to them, too many fat tails"

> "Not having fear and cutting positions when they are going against you speak to a willingness to take risk and an ability to control risk." — Schwager

### Developing an Edge

- **Must be on right side of market** to make money — how to get an edge?
- Went back to facts: If you know buyer for XYZ stock at some price below market, "you know one fact"
- **Check what happened last time market got to this level** — use charts
- **Volume as screen** for what stocks to look at
- Thought process: *"There is lots of volume. Something is going on. Can I develop a view from that?"*

**Chart philosophy**:
- "Charts are simply a record of how things have traded in the past. That's it."
- Not a big believer in chart analysis
- "It is extremely appealing to think that you can take a data set from the past and predict what will happen in the future. It is very attractive because as a human being you are always looking for certainty."
- "You can never start with the chart. To say that you can predict the future from past data is patently untrue."
- "You can talk about percentage probabilities of what might happen next, but you can't go any further than that."
- Combined charts with other facts: where orders were, market volume

### Lehman Brothers Transition

- Left Warburg after **two and half years** — only paid £13,000/year despite being best trader
- **Lehman Brothers** offered £50,000/year job
- Returned to Warburg with better offer
- Warburg: "We can put you at £28,000... We have all these tiers, and you are a trainee."
- Clark: "Why £28,000? Why not £50,000?"
- Thought tiers were "total bullshit" — went to Lehman

**Warburg vs. Lehman**:
- **Warburg was number one rated** — rich in order flow information
- At Lehman, **couldn't make a penny** — "terrible shock to my ego"
- "I had no idea how to make money outside of the Warburg environment, which was so rich in order flow information."

**Edge came from knowledge of where orders were**: The franchise provided opportunity, but outperformance came from using order flow information better than others

### Lehman Struggles and Recovery

- "Very depressing time. It lasted for several months."
- Seen this happen to many traders — "When you find that you can't make any money, smaller and smaller losses take on greater and greater emotional significance, and you lose all perspective."

**Incident with Novo (Danish company)**:
- Playing basketball, got call: **Novo** up $2 from European close
- Asked if stock was bid — 100,000 shares bid
- **Gut reaction**: Went short entire amount — "biggest position I had taken by a mile"
- Reverted to old Warburg mode: brain calculated risk and just did the trade

**Why good risk**:
- Up $2 from close, "which was a big move for a stock that didn't move that much. It was just a gut reaction."
- Came in next morning, bought stock back for **$100,000 profit**
- From that moment: "I couldn't stop making money"

**New edge without order flow**:
- Developed strong relationships with other brokers — used their order flow information
- Also trading news flow
- Started screening for volume or story — "my trading was good enough so that if I could find volume or a story, I could trade it"

### Reading *Market Wizards*

- **Seminal moment**: Reading Schwager's *Market Wizards*
- Thought: *"That is what I do. That is one of my rules."*
- "Like these people had copied what I do. How could they know?"
- **Awakening**: "For the first time in my life I realized that I had a method."
- Before: "I thought I was playing a videogame, and I couldn't believe I was getting paid to do it."
- "The one thing that I really took away from your book was that once you understand you have a method, you can tweak that method."

**Advice to traders**:
> "Do more of what works and less of what doesn't." — Clark's core advice

- Young traders: "I have been running this book, and these things have been going really well, but I keep losing money on this."
- Clark: "Just stop doing the things that are not working."
- "Dissect your P&L and see what works for you and what doesn't. It is a very interesting process to analyze where your profits come from, and traders often don't know."

### Transition to Event-Driven Trading

- **After reading *Market Wizards***: Analyzed where he made money
- **Had series of arbitrage trades where had an edge** — started looking for more arbitrage trades

**Focus on arbitrage**:
- Wasn't doing badly anywhere, "but the arbitrage trades were by far the most consistent and profitable"
- Really only one big loss trade: **1912DS** (Danish shipping company)

**1912DS disaster**:
- Traded at extremely high share price: **140,000 Danish kroner**
- Traded in lots of one share or five shares
- Clark became bullish, bought a lot
- Article in paper: **Company was a fraud**
- Bought at 140,000, **opened next day at 100,000 offered, nothing bid**
- Sick feeling: "That's too big; I can't show that today."
- **Wrote down price a little bit every day for next three months** while trading hard to make money
- Stock didn't trade — literally no trades, no bids
- No settlement price anywhere — "Wild West. Traders marked their own book. No one checked it. Smoothing losses was the status quo."

**Ultimate loss and lesson**:
- Sold somewhere higher than 100,000 (doesn't remember exactly)
- Article turned out to be "total nonsense"
- **Key lesson**: "Price is irrelevant; it is size that kills you."
- "If you are too big in an illiquid stock, there is no way out. I wanted to cut the position, but I couldn't."
- **Other lesson**: "This trade taught me is to focus on what works."
- Was just a punt — bought because thought momentum would carry it up
- "After that trade, I became much more focused on just looking for arbitrage trades, which was where I was making most of my money."

<!-- pp. 261-280 -->

## Chapter 9: Colm O'Shea (continued)

### Transition to First New York Securities

- O'Shea was doing **directional risk arbitrage** at First New York Securities — flexibly choosing whether to hedge, go long both sides, or not hedge depending on the situation
- Started his own asset management business in UK in 2001 with an **event-driven fund**, continuing to manage First New York Securities money part-time alongside his fund
- When his fund grew to nearly **$1 billion**, he told First New York Securities he was too busy to maintain advisory role
- Gave parting advice to firm head: "You are too old. You're killing your own business. Get out."

### First New York Securities' Missed Opportunity

- The founder held on too tight after 25 years of proprietary trading with no losing years
- Despite perfect track record, they **missed the entire growth in asset management** during the hedge fund era
- Founder was getting too old to take risks — admitted it himself
- O'Shea agreed to become managing member to modernize the firm: needed efficiency, technology, outside money management
- The trade: fix the company, be involved for a period, get much more value for it

### O'Shea's Existential Struggles

- Still waiting to figure out what he wants to do when he grows up — "quite depressing"
- Hasn't built anything despite financial success
- Gives money away; staying because couldn't figure out anything better to do at the time

> "But what have I achieved? I haven't built anything."

- **Trading offers no career**: "You are only as good as your last trade, and that is it. You build nothing; you just trade... So what you have spent doing for X hours every working day of your life has ended, and there is nothing left to show for it, except for money."
- Very nihilistic view, but that's how he feels at 47, still trying to decide what he wants to do

### The Transition from Joy to Imprisonment

- Trading was fun when he could walk away
- When you have a business, you can't walk away — becomes a prison
- Took on more business responsibility by becoming managing member, ironically losing freedom

### Psychology of Trading: Position Sizing

- **Entry size more important than entry price** — if size is right, you're much more likely to stay with a winning trade
- Traders often plan to scale down as losers (buy at 8, add at 7, 6, 5) — but if you'll be "puking your guts out" at lower levels, you shouldn't be buying at all at 8
- If you can't handle the volatility, scale down to 25% of intended size

> "It is the size of the position you put on rather than the price at which you put it on that determines your ability to keep the position."

- First lesson from first boss: **price is irrelevant; it's all about controlling position size**
- **Liquidity is critical** — when merger deal breaks, cut position immediately to get a pocket of liquidity, even at lower level
- If you wait, liquidity dries up and you're left with an outsized position in what becomes a directional trade

### Common Trader Mistakes

- Traders from **information-rich environments** (big investment banks) struggle when they come to trading houses with no information flow
- Trading in a vacuum — incredibly strong traders in big size suddenly can't make money, even lose a bit
- Becomes downward spiral: trade smaller and smaller, every dollar lost becomes emotionally more important, lose all perspective
- Many never had a plan; just responded to stimuli around them
- Advice: **replace the information flow** — draw up list of 20 contacts and phone them every day
- They don't take the advice

### Advice for Struggling Traders

- Find things to involve yourself in — very good to be busy when you're a prop trader
- Don't want too much time to stare at the screen, especially if your style has limited positions
- Coming back to investment bank world: meetings and activities suck up time, but actually **limit time in front of screens staring at positions**
- Don't want to be sitting in front of screen staring at market prices for 12 hours a day — will start to overprocess and overtrade

### Patience as a Common Denominator

- Successful traders exhibit **patience, particularly regarding staying with good trades long enough**
- True regardless of time frame, even for daytraders
- The more time staring at screen, the less patience you'll have
- In negative loop, every downtick cuts you — you feel physical pain with every tick against you

### When Trading Edge Disappears

- O'Shea has had several occasions thinking: *"I am never going to make a penny again. I am crap. I have always been crap. I have just been found out."*
- Even after making money for 10 years, can still get into that mind-set

> "You had a knack for trading, but now it is gone. You lost it."

> "I lost it. I was never that good. It was just the market. Now the market is changed, and I don't know what to do. It is a horrible, horrible feeling."

### Discipline: Taking Breaks When Out of Sync

- When in that mode, **don't do anything**
- Discipline yourself not to trade for two weeks or whatever time period
- **Take a holiday** — must get out of everything first, then go away and forget about it
- Takes time because what you'll do for first few days is torture yourself ("I could have done this. I could have done that.")
- After a few days, can let it go and unwind
- When you come back, set rules: won't trade for two weeks, will see trades itching to do but need discipline not to do them — clearly not in sync with markets

### Returning from Break: Start Small

- When ready to begin trading again, see a trade you really like, **trade a fraction of the size you'd normally trade**
- At least half the time, trade may go your way initially, then go against you — all you're experiencing is a feel for the next few ticks
- You need to set rules to be able to say you won't trade for two weeks
- See trades but need discipline — otherwise wouldn't be where you are
- When you feel ready and see trade you really like, at least half the time it will go against you because all you may be experiencing is feel for next few ticks

### High Volume as Trading Signal

- O'Shea's son inquires about his trading style — mentions **high volume** as one thing he looks for
- At Lehman when short on information, O'Shea would **filter for European stocks with unusually large volume**
- Then go through charts to see if any were making interesting bottoms
- Would call contacts and ask what they knew about those specific stocks
- **Volume is incredibly important** — found it to be very valuable indicator

### Using Volume in Practice

- If stock has been bombed out and there's sudden jump in volume, doesn't mean buy straight away (can go quiet again)
- But clearly somebody is beginning to buy
- Then watch for signs stock is **resilient on down days** in market, suggesting underlying buying support
- Begin to nibble away at establishing position
- Sometimes stock will see a day where all of sudden it just gaps up, and you trade to catch that gap
- Have to do fundamental work to find out what's going on — don't want to buy a stock headed for zero
- **Volume is just a way of identifying potentially interesting situations**

### The Importance of Calling People

- Need to be willing to call people to get information
- "You need to ask the next question. You never know what you will find out that will be useful."

### Example: FCC Approval Trade

- Merger deal had to be approved by FCC, nothing was happening, spread kept widening and widening
- Getting more concerned about position
- **Kept calling FCC over and over again** until one time, by luck, got secretary of one of commissioners
- Secretary said: "Oh, that; it's on his desk ready to be signed, but he is away fishing this week."

### Example: Banker Funding Question

- On phone with banker regarding funding for a deal
- Kept asking him a question he couldn't answer in 10 different ways, knowing full well he couldn't answer
- After call, said "**Sell it now**" — many things would have been reasonable for him to say, but he didn't
- Couldn't say funding was done or not done, but could have said work in progress or they were confident
- All he said to each question: "I can't answer that question"
- If you don't make the phone call, if you don't ask the next question, you will never know

### Trade Example: Fiat 2003

- Made **20% in a month** on single transaction
- Broad market rallying sharply in rebound from preceding bear market
- **Fiat had big rights issue** — at same time, **Deutsche Bank announced disposing of industrial holdings**, and Fiat was one of their positions
- Rather than exercise rights (which would increase position), Deutsche Bank decided to sell their rights
- Market going up, and while Fiat should have been going same way, it was actually going down because of big seller
- Seller was not driven by fundamentals, but by desire to rebalance portfolio to reduce industrial holdings
- **Rights were especially cheap** because of Deutsche Bank selling
- Buying the Fiat rights was trade where everything lined up:
  1. Market was very strong
  2. Stock was substantially underperforming market and sector for two technical reasons (rights issue + large seller) that had nothing to do with fundamentals
  3. Rights provided way to put on large position for small capital outlay
  4. Because Deutsche Bank was large seller of rights and stock was difficult to borrow, rights were trading below intrinsic value

### Advice to Aspiring Traders

- First, need to make sure they **understand their motivation**
- Not everyone who says they want to be trader really does
- Trading has **macho mystique** — people will say they want to be trader and won't admit wanting to be analyst, even if they'd be happier and make more money as analyst

### Characteristics of Successful Traders

- **All work hard** — example: First New York trader in New Zealand trading international equities who "can't be awake 24 hours a day, but he seems to be"
- Nearly all successful traders are **one-trick ponies** — do one thing very well
- When they stray from single focus, often ends in disaster
- In hedge fund world, traders do one thing, make lot of money, then think: *"This one thing is rather boring. I can do other things because I am a genius."*
- So they start doing other things — had number of great macro traders decide to branch into multistrategy funds
- Didn't work too well in 2008 when they were all exposed
- One well-known macro trader wrote to investors in 2008 that he had made them money, but it was all the other managers in fund, trading assortment of strategies, who lost all the money
- **Managers diversify away from expertise because they have made a lot of money and think they can do anything**

### Why Traders Deviate from What Works

- Deep down inside they know they are one-trick ponies, and that one thing could end
- But successful traders who are one-trick ponies, when that trick stops, they learn another trick
- Some traders will change while one trick is still working and destroy it
- **Need to be a bit obsessive** to do same thing 10 hours a day
- People who are obsessive can become very good traders

### Other Traits of Successful Traders

- **Capable of changing their mind in an instant**
- Can be dogmatic in opinion then immediately change it

> "This market is going higher. It's absolutely going up. No, it's definitely going down."

- If you can't do that, you will get caught in a position and be wiped out

### Example: Euro Disney Mind Change

- Perfect example: **Euro Disney** listing in US many years ago
- Already listed in Europe, but Blue Sky laws required waiting period before US listing
- Taylor built up large position in anticipation of burst of retail demand when it became available to US retail investors
- On first day available to US retail investors, had buy orders for millions of shares
- That morning, already very long, but put in buy orders to get more long
- Market gapped higher on opening and started racing away on upside
- Weren't getting filled on anything because there was so little for sale
- Market moving up in gaps with very little volume
- **In an instant, completely switched orders and started selling whatever he could**

### What Flipped Him Around?

- Recognized in moment of clarity: if he had reached fever pitch trying to buy at any price, the moment market turned, it would just head straight down

### The Aftermath

- It fell about **10% from that point that day**, kept going down in following days
- Everyone had done same thing — all come in long in anticipation of influx of retail buy orders

### Catalyst for Change: London and Overseas Freight

- Something clicked — he was hysterical
- Before 1987 crash, was on desk with experienced traders, rumor circulated to buy small stock called **London and Overseas Freight**
- Stock started day at £.10, bought at £.12
- Stock kept going up all through day: £.13, £.14, £.15, £.16...
- Guys on desk who hadn't bought couldn't stand pain of not being in, they got long
- Stock just kept going higher and higher
- Finally, one trader who had not bought stock was on squawk box to floor saying: **"Where is it now?"** Answer: "It's at 22."

> "I don't care what I have to pay, just get me in!"

- He got filled at £.23, never traded higher, closed day at £.12
- Stock eventually went to nothing — was just a microcosm of hysteria
- Might have been his recognition of same type of hysteria in himself years later that triggered about-face in Euro Disney
- May have even said to broker: "Just get me stock! Just get me stock!" And something clicked: *I have been here before. I have seen this.*

### Low Volatility Track Record

- Extremely low volatility versus most other event-driven funds
- **Have to be able to cut your position** — will never accept anybody saying they can't cut a position

### Managing Through 2007-2008

- In 2007, got rid of anything directional or long dated
- Put almost all money in **short duration risk arbitrage** — deals felt almost certain to close with very wide spreads because of market volatility
- Ability of companies to close transactions had not been degraded by what was happening in world
- Only risk was something might happen causing prime brokers to change margin requirements, forcing liquidation
- Thought only way that would happen: some more major market distress
- To hedge this possibility, **bought out-of-the-money puts on S&P and sold out-of-the-money calls to pay for puts**
- If market went sideways or up, would do very well because of core portfolio
- If market went down suddenly, still felt core portfolio would hold up, and puts would provide protection against change in margin requirements
- In 2008, world had changed — **volatility quadrupled**
- Decided should trade **fraction of what used to trade** — most people didn't do that and got blown up

### Cutting Exposure in 2008

- Had good month, then another very good month, started next month very strong
- Two days later, were down for the month — nothing had happened
- Could just smell had to cut positions
- **Took off 75% of exposure**

### Not Gradual Reduction

- "Oh, no. I don't believe in this idea, *We will sell 25 percent of our position and then think about it.*"

### Importance of Gut Feel

- **Absolutely** — learned to trust judgment
- Gut feel is important, and you can trade off it, but need set of rules controlling size and stop loss points

### Trading Rules O'Shea Lives By

1. **If you wake up thinking about a position, it's too big**
2. **Never stop asking questions** — speak to as many people as you can, research every opposing opinion
3. **When everything lines up, you need to swing for it** — in those situations, even if wrong, probably won't be wrong by that much. But if position starts behaving in way you don't understand, need to cut it because then you clearly don't know what is going on. The market is telling you that you don't know.

### Philosophy About Markets

- The market is not about facts; it's all about **people's opinions and positions**
- Consequently, anything can be at any price, any time
- Once you understand that, you realize you need to have **protective stops**

### Any Final Words?

> "Your job as a trader is to make the line go from bottom left to top right. That's it. If the line has gone too much or too long, you were wrong. You can't argue that the market is wrong because it is your job to predict every move in the market."

- Had managers in 2008 who lost 50%, in some cases even 80%
- Why? Because they couldn't accept they were wrong
- Kept doing the math, kept saying they were right
- Missed the point: their math might have been right, but their job isn't to do the math; their job is to **trade what is in front of them**
- Had guys saying they were right, market was wrong, and they had billions of dollars of embedded value in portfolio
- Their job isn't to create billions of dollars of embedded value; their job is to **make the line go from bottom left to top right**
- Once you understand that is your job as trader, you have to start **protecting the direction of the line**

---

## Chapter 10: Martin Taylor — The Tsar Has No Clothes

### Background and Performance

- Most hedge fund managers seek to grow assets — **Martin Taylor chose the reverse course**
- Ten years after launching with **$20 million seed capital**, assets grew to over **$7 billion**
- Taylor notified investors he was **closing fund in 12 months** — at time when NAV was near all-time high with consistent outperformance
- Decided other considerations mattered more than maximizing earnings
- Coordinated closing with opening of new fund that **capped assets at less than one-quarter of previous fund's size**
- Hedge manager voluntarily cutting assets by more than 75% is **rarity, if not singular event**

### Performance Record

- May well have **best performance record in emerging markets**
- Between 1995 and early 2000, managed **long-only fund** focused on East European equities
- After five-month hiatus, launched **hedge fund** in October 2000
- Named after **Alexander Nevsky** — thirteenth-century Russian hero who defended country against outside invaders (not objectionable figure to neighboring East European countries)
- Initially focused on East European equities, by 2003 broadened to **global emerging markets**
- Across entire track record (1995-2011): achieved average annual compounded net return of **over 27%**, more than doubling the **12% return of corresponding emerging markets index**
- During 11-year hedge fund history: average annual compounded net return over **22%**, more than doubling corresponding **10% return of HFRI Emerging Markets index**

### Superior Risk-Adjusted Returns

- Achieved substantially higher returns while having **much smaller drawdowns** than both long-only and hedge fund emerging market indexes
- Was the **only long-only manager to avoid a loss in 1998**
- Did extremely well during 2000-2002 bear market: hedge fund up **27% annualized** during period
- Only losing year was 2008, but even then loss was **less than one-third the long-only index decline and 40% of hedge fund index loss**

### Interview Setting

- Interviewed Taylor at his home in **suburb of London**
- Reached on pleasant walk from train station, passing through town park on sunny, breezy Saturday morning in late April
- Talked in living room, sitting beneath large English impressionistic painting aptly named *Harvest Storm*
- Taylor dressed casually in shorts and T-shirt, ready to depart for weekend
- Family had left for trip to grandparents about an hour into conversation
- Taylor graciously scheduled to leave later, planning to catch afternoon train
- Estimated would need at least three hours — conversation lasted **more than five hours** and could easily have carried on longer
- Both conscious of his delayed departure
- One chunk of conversation regarding Russia proved unusable (Taylor capped that portion: "You know, you can't use any of that. Russia is not a country where you want to make enemies.")

<!-- pp. 281-300 -->

## Russia 1998 Crisis - Deep Dive

### Discovery of Russian Balance of Payments Fraud

- **Taylor became bearish on Russia ~1 year before August 1998 collapse**
- Took fund to **40% cash** — extraordinary move for long-only fund
- **No one else** was discussing the balance of payments discrepancy

**The fraud mechanism:**
- Russia showed **current account surplus** on paper, but **reserves were declining** (should have been increasing 10-11% of GDP yearly)
- **Russian exports massively overstated** in cash terms
  - Example: Mining company exports $100M raw materials, reports sale as $50M
  - Missing $50M → private Swiss account
  - $40M of reported $50M also → Swiss account
  - Only fraction received as cash in Russia
- **Capital flight** created massive black hole in capital account
- **Yeltsin-era theft** of company assets was pervasive — numbers didn't add up

**Why companies didn't collapse despite 90% theft:**
- Ran **token systems** — workers paid in company store tokens (Victorian England model)
- Company owned housing, stores, football team — everything in single-employer towns
- Workers had **no choice, no money** spent on infrastructure
- **Voucher privatization scheme:** Management bought vouchers from workers for pennies on the dollar after Soviet Union fell

### October 1997: The Pivot

**Catalyst:** Yeltsin health rumor → market crashed **23% in one session**

**Taylor's response:**
- **Started selling aggressively** despite 30% bounce next day
- Recognized the **bull market spell was broken** — when trending markets break, bad news suddenly matters
- Market finished +24% that day, but Taylor was right to sell because fundamentals were "very ugly indeed"

> "When markets are trending up strongly, and there is bad news, the bad news counts for nothing. But if there is a break that reminds people what it is like to lose money in equities, then suddenly the buying is not mindless anymore."

### February 1998: Staying Bearish

- Market down **50%** by February 1998
- Taylor **resisted pressure** to reinstate long positions despite typical "buy the dip" logic
- Wrote internal paper: **"The Tsar Has No Clothes"** (title plagiarized for chapter heading)

> "Russia's problems are unlikely to be tackled until a serious ruble crisis jolts them out of their complacency. This leaves significant further downside for the equity market. We must remain underweight."

**Why international funds were long:**
- **40% short rates** on GKOs (ruble T-bills)
- Perception: nuclear-armed Russia "too big to fail"
- But: **Smart money was domestic, not international** — Russians put money in Switzerland

### Summer 2008: The Final Catalyst

**Goldman Sachs Eurobond deal** (early summer 2008):
- Managed sale of **$25B low-yielding, dollar-denominated Russian sovereign 10-year Eurobonds**
- Purpose: Allow Russia to retire similar amount of high-yielding GKOs
- Bonds immediately **fell steadily from day one**
- Foreign reserves should have **doubled** ($20B → $25B), but only increased **$3B**
- **"The emperor has no clothes" moment** — forced recognition of capital accounts data fraud
- Money likely: received by officials, divvied up, sent to Switzerland

### August 1998: Why Taylor Still Lost Despite Being Out of Russia

**40% cash position, but:**
- Invested portion held **high-beta stocks** (1.5+ beta)
- Good quality companies **still declined 70-80%** because widely owned
- These companies continued **30% earnings growth** → prices shot back up when market stabilized
- **Being 40% cash allowed buying in September** after crash
- Portfolio rebounded with "insane beta" → **finished 1998 slightly up despite index down 30%**

**Why not low-beta stocks?**

> "Buying low-beta stocks is a common mistake investors make. Why would you ever want to own boring stocks? If the market goes down 40 percent for macro reasons, they'll go down 20 percent. Wouldn't you just rather own cash?"

- Low-beta = **"pigeon-and-elephant trade"** — eat like pigeon, shit like elephant
- To get equity-like returns from boring stocks, must **leverage up** → losses become massively asymmetric
- Emerging market bonds inherently unattractive — coupon if all goes well, lose everything if default

**Core philosophy:**
- **Always high-beta stocks balanced by cash or shorts**
- "Boring companies never have the opportunity for earnings growth"

## Emerging Markets: Macro vs. Company-Level Analysis

### Individual Stock Selection Is Critical

**Macro unpredictability:**
- 50 macro experts = 55 opinions
- Can build **much more knowledge about a company** than macro outlook
- Meet/talk with every company owned every few months over years

**Three elements for stock purchase:**
1. **Favorable macro situation**
2. **Secular trend**
3. **Good company management**

**Example: Russian mobile companies 1999-2005**
- Largest trade ever in Russia
- **Macro:** 80% ruble devaluation (1998) + oil rebound from $12 → favorable balance of payments, foreign reserves surge
- **Secular trend:** Mobile penetration increasing 25% annually, massive purchasing power increase
- **Company quality:** Good management, transparent accounting, good disclosure

### Why Leave Barings? (Middle of 1999)

**Three key frustrations:**
1. **Negative impact of large assets on performance** — $2B in tiny East European market was "insane"
2. **Inability to go short** — long-only constraint
3. **Failure to financially benefit from outperformance** — paid "trivial amount" despite accounting for 30% of firm's P&L

**Result:** Joined **Thames River** (umbrella company for hedge funds) September 2000
- Best long-only emerging markets track record by wide margin
- Raised only **$20M** initially

### Launch Challenges (September 2000)

**Started 40% net long, market down 20% → fund down 6% first month**

Immediate investor complaints: "You can't lose 6 percent in one month"

Taylor's response: "Fine, if you don't like it, take your money away"

**Second month:** Only $100K new investment — fair-weather investors fled

**Stuck to guns → up 8% December, finished quarter up 2%**

**Key lesson to new investors:**

> "You will lose money investing with me at various points in the year, and it will always be unpleasant when it happens. This health warning is crucial so that investors have proper expectations."

**Reality check:**
- Annualized volatility 20-40% → **inevitably 2-3 decent hits to NAV each year**
- If can't live with monthly drawdowns, will sell in panic near lows
- **Psychologically impaired** regarding that position → never buy back, miss subsequent upside
- **Nevsky fund has had 6-12% intramonth losses every year it's been running**

## Position Sizing and Risk Management

### Normal Net Exposure Range

**20% net long to 110% net long**

**Philosophy:**
- If completely out when market reverses, **never get back in**
- Maintains **some net long exposure even when bearish**

**Example (Q1 2009):**
- Very bearish, but **20% net long**
- When market reversed in March, mentally easy to double to 40% because already made money on rebound
- If had been net short waiting for pullback, pullback never came

### Contrarian Timing Advice

> "When the market is so bad that you think it is obvious that you should be net short, that's typically the time when it is all in the price and you should be buying."

**Market strategists problem:**
- Brokers' strategists recommend extreme overweight/underweight, then wrong for 2-3 years
- Would have capital wiped out if managing hedge fund
- **"Managing money is real life, not some bullshit strategist fantasy world"**

**Taylor's approach:**
- When market up: try to capture **70-80% of move**
- When market down: try to lose only **30-40% of it**

**Dogmatic positioning danger:**
- Many hedge funds brilliant in 2008 (short all year) **then blew up in 2009**

### One-Trick Pony Criticism

**Unnamed hedge fund manager** (stayed short 2008 when markets up 40-50%):
- Did "one good trade" — short in 2008
- But stayed short through year when up 40-50% → out of business by year-end
- "Did what market strategists do at a brokerage house, but he did it with client money. You can't do that."

> "You have to always be pragmatic enough to move with the market. You always need to be facing in the right direction."

## 2000-2002 Performance and 2008 Crisis

### Early Success (2000-2002)

**27% annualized return** (October 2000-2002) vs. <3% for HFRI emerging markets index and net losses for long-only EM indexes

**Key factors:**
- **Underweighting tech stocks and high-beta bubbles** (Turkey) — thought worthless at stupid multiples
- **Heavily invested in Russia** — cheap ruble + firm oil prices provided stimulus

### 2008: The Only Losing Year

**Emerging markets down 54%, Taylor down 17%** — exactly in line with investor expectations (capture 30-40% of downside)

**Entry into 2008:**
- Very bullish end of 2007
- Positioned **85% net long high-beta stocks, 200% gross exposure**
- Troubled by **widening credit spreads** (reminiscent of August 2007) → cut to **40% net long**
- **Aggressively selling first week of January was critical** — up 4% at midyear

### Why January Selling Was Crucial

**Stocks sold in early January were higher at end of Q2** — would have looked "stupid" in hindsight

**But Taylor argues it was brilliant:**
- If hadn't sold early January, would have sold at "bloody lows" → down 15% in January instead of 5%
- Wouldn't have had any position in February-March when market rallied
- **Drastically cutting exposure early positioned fund to buy on SocGen collapse**
- "If we had been nursing a 15 percent loss, we could never have taken the risk of buying on the break"

### Second Half 2008 Losses

**Despite macro weakness, maintained net long exposure:**
- Developed countries: GDP flattening, fundamentals ugly
- **Emerging market companies: earnings up sharply, valuations attractive**
- Compromised with **moderate 40% net long exposure**
- After Lehman → reduced to **20% net long**

**20% net long instead of flat helped avoid "getting whipsawed" by extreme peaks/troughs in Q4 2008:**
- Three rallies of **15-20% all ended up being followed by new lows**
- If dumped entire position after 15-20% rally, would have jumped back in, then thought "Oh my God, this is the turn" at next low
- **Might have lost more going flat** due to subsequent sharp rallies

### Investor Response to First Losing Year

**No redemptions until October 2008**

**Fund became "cash machine":**
- Golden rule: **only liquid securities** → remained open for monthly dealing unchanged
- Most peers in distress, gated funds
- Fund-of-fund investors had capital withdrawn by clients → had to sell
- **First 8 years (Oct 2008-March 2009): nearly half of assets redeemed**
- **Within 3 months: all money came back** as markets stabilized
- Forced to close fund once more

## Long-Only vs. Hedge Fund Management

### Comparison

**Long-only:** "Really easy"
- If up more than index, everyone loves you (85% of managers underperform)
- Even when lose (as long as less than index in relative terms), people still love you

**Hedge fund:** Demanding expectations
- When market up: investors want you to perform like market or better
- When market down: investors want you to perform like cash

### Why 85% of Long-Only EM Managers Underperform

1. **High management fees** (100-200 bps typical)
2. **High volatility → poor decisions** (panic selling near bottom, FOMO buying near top)
3. **Frequent index composition changes** → selling dropped stocks under widespread selling pressure
4. **Emerging markets behave irrationally** — large local retail investor percentage makes irrational decisions based on rumors/conspiracy theories

**Example of irrationality:**
- "Two or three times as many local emerging market investors would think the World Trade Center towers were brought down by the CIA rather than by Al Qaeda"

### Foreign vs. Local Investors

**Common belief:** Foreign investors dominant in emerging markets

**Taylor's correction:**
- Foreign investors dominant around **cycle turning points**
- Over longer periods, **key price moves influenced by local investors and rumor of the day**
- Can short on terrible fundamental news, then stock keeps rising on "wild, unfounded rumor that the son of the president is going to buy the company out"

### Why Long-Only EM Funds Persist Despite Underperformance

**Marketing trumps performance:**
- **Mark Mobius example:** Massively underperformed index over 20 years
- But always in papers visiting/opining on EM companies/governments
- **Investment advisers heavily influenced by media image** → suck clients into funds

**Other reasons:**
- Even index funds underperform due to high fees
- Investors not looking at relative performance — if EM up 10%/year average and he's up 6%, "just looking at the fact that their investment is up"

## 2010 Fund Restructuring

### Why Reduce Assets?

**By February 2010:** $20M → $7.5B ($3.5B hedge fund, $4B long-only)

**Three motivations:**
1. Time-consuming nature of trading around core positions (5am-9pm every day)
2. Fund grown very large with big team (3 people → 35 people)
3. Eventually going to "kill myself" from workload

**Decision:** Shrink fund to **20% of former client base** (February 2010)

### Forced Liquidation Structure

**Method:**
- Close original fund
- Simultaneously reopen new fund
- Gave clients **one-year notice** that original fund would be closing

**Purpose:** Give flexibility to change investment style

### Investment Style Changes

**Original hedge fund commitment:**
- At least **50% in emerging markets** always
- If no Asia exposure and Asia went mental, clients might sue for incompetence

**New fund freedom:**
- Can do anything
- If don't like Asia and want more sleep, can choose **no Asia exposure**
- "I'm also trying to get away from that tyranny in hedge funds: monthly performance"

**Old structure problem:**
- Many clients were **fund-of-funds driven by monthly data**
- Obsession with monthly returns → **poor long-term investment decisions**

**New structure:**
- Still report monthly returns
- Quarterly newsletter (instead of monthly)
- "Trying to stop caring about what my clients think"
- Freedom to maintain long-term investment focus vs. monthly relative performance concerns

## Current Portfolio Example: Apple (April 2011)

### Investment Thesis

**20% of portfolio in Apple**

**Contrarian element:**
- **U.S. analysts think limited growth potential** due to large U.S. market share
- Fail to appreciate: **300M people in U.S., 6.7B in rest of world**

**China opportunity:**
- Highest approval rating: **China (900M mobile subscribers)**
- Currently sold: **3M iPhones in China**
- **Unique OS and excellent hardware** = barriers to entry vs. competitors

**Forecast:**
- Over next 4 years: **Apple will repeat U.S. success globally**
- Forecasting earnings **50-60% above street** for next 3-4 years

**Valuation:**
- Trading **16x forward prospective earnings (2011)**
- Based on 2014 forecasted earnings: only **4.8x earnings**
- One of fastest-growing companies globally
- Best management teams
- **<5x earnings** on future projections
- **$150B net cash** by 2014 (nearly half market cap)

**Position:** 20% of portfolio

### Why Apple Hasn't Performed Better?

**Reasons for current underperformance:**
- Gone up a lot → investors think expensive
- All U.S. analysts focused on: **next iPhone may be delayed a few months**
- Think delay is bad — Taylor: "It is not bad at all"

**Apple's brilliance: execution**
- Would they prefer Apple rush out next iPhone and do what **RIMM** did with **PlayBook** (BlackBerry tablet)?
  - "One of the most suicidal pieces of rubbish ever put out"
  - "RIMM will probably go bust in the next three or four years"

**RIMM's fatal error:**
- Incompetent product launches
- Bringing out corporate-targeted tablet **you can't even use for e-mail**
- "Producing a car with no engine or wheels. It is literally as bad as that"
- Rushed to market because **iPad 2 breaking into corporate market**
- Worried if didn't compete with iPad 2, would lose corporate market
- **What they've done is guarantee they will lose the corporate market** by undermining every IT manager who argued for BlackBerry over iPhone

**Market impact post-interview:**
- Interviewed April 30, 2011: Apple $350, RIMM $49
- March 19, 2012 (production): Apple $601, RIMM <$15

## Short Selling Strategy

### Long vs. Short Approach

**Longs:**
- Cheap relative to sector
- Positive earnings surprises expected next few years

**Shorts:**
- Expensive relative to sector
- Negative earnings surprises expected

**Problem:** Bad companies = **greatest takeover risk**

**Emerging markets takeover dynamics:**
- Full of sectors dominated by multinationals wanting exposure
- Only companies they can take over are **bad companies**
- Need to triangulate: company, government, regulator
- **Much more difficult** for foreign firm to get approval for takeover of **well-performing local company** (authorities fear "selling out" to foreigners)
- **Bad company:** government/regulators more likely to approve (seen as "saving company and saving jobs")

**Result:**
- Can be **long good stock at 7x earnings, short bad stock at 15x earnings**
- Stupid foreign company pays **50% premium** to buy bad company

### Solution: Short Index Futures

**Half to three-quarters of shorts = stock index futures**

**Net exposure adjustment done through shorting markets rather than individual companies**

### Managing Individual Company Shorts Given Takeover Risk

**Only short bad companies that can't be taken over:**
- **Government-owned**
- **Pension fund-owned**
- Will never be sold — workers afraid acquiring company would sack 20% of labor force

**In emerging markets:** ~**1/3 of all companies are government or pension fund owned**

## Risk Management Philosophy

### Core Principles

**Always most liquid securities** — if wrong, get out immediately

**Research intensive:**
- Forecast earnings **3-4 years out** for every stock
- Forecast macro picture **3-4 years out**

**Pragmatism:**
- "I am wrong all the time"
- "If I can be right 60 percent of the time, and when I am right I have some big winners, and when I am wrong, I staunch the losses quickly, I can make a lot of money"

### No Quantitative Risk Control

**Never use quantitative risk control models:**

> "All quantitative risk control models use historical volatility. It is like driving by looking in the rearview mirror. If you use volatility as a guideline, and volatility suddenly increases, you will—Doh!—find that your risk was much greater than you thought, but by then you will already have been wiped out."

**What happened to managers in 2008**

**Also never use stops**

### Common Sense Risk Management Instead

**Multiple requirements for trade:**
- Do we like the company?
- Is it cheap?
- Does it generate cash flow?
- Do we trust management?
- Do I have confidence in my projections?
- Is macro outlook favorable?

**If company meets all criteria:**
- Determine **appropriate position size** given company and country risk
- Very risky → **1-5% of portfolio**
- Lower risk with very high confidence → **up to 20% of portfolio** (e.g., Apple)

**Accept Steve Jobs risk:** Stock could go down 2% if anything happened → can live with it because think stock will triple over 4 years

**Sector concentration limits:**
- If 20% position in Apple, **can't have another significant position in same industry sector**
- Negative shock might impact entire sector rather than being Apple-specific

**Team dynamics:**
- Very important to have people whose opinions you respect
- Can push back at ideas in way that makes you stop, listen, test own views
- **Partner Nick Barnes is crucial** to this regard

**Footnote:** Steve Jobs died ~6 months after interview; Apple stock moved higher after event

## Projection Methodology

### Why Projections Differ from Market

**Common denominator: trend market doesn't appreciate**

**Apple examples:**

1. **Never had consequential sales in India or China** → street assumes never will (imbecilic)

2. **iPad sales extrapolation error:**
   - Q4 last year: sold 7.3M iPads
   - Street forecast this year: **29.5M units**
   - Just took Q4 sales and annualized them
   - Failed to account: **Apple revolutionized existing product already way ahead of competition**
   - Not only much better product, but **Steve Jobs priced competitively instead of at premium**
   - Apple's economies of scale → **no one else can even possibly compete**
   - Taylor forecast: **40M this year, 60M next year** (street forecast next year: 40M)
   - "It is not rocket science; it is just common sense"

### Role of Technical Analysis

**Charts very important** — but as supplemental tool

**Usage for entries:**
- After fundamental work, look at chart before buying
- If stock very overbought, won't stop from buying, but **will start with small position**
- Larger chance of correction if overbought
- If put on entire position then stock has large correction, "would feel terrible"

**Scaling in:**
- Really like company, want 10% of portfolio
- If stock extremely overbought → start with only **1% position**
- If keeps going up → "happy that I bought at least some"
- More willing to buy more because bought part at lower price
- If didn't initially buy anything because overbought → "would be a dreadful mistake"

**Checking for selling pressure:**
- Decide to buy based on fundamentals, then check chart
- If massively underperformed relative to market → **check who has been selling**
- Price weakness might indicate **all fundamental research is worthless because management has lied**

**Charts as confirmation tool:**
- Use to add to positions
- If bullish on stock but don't have full position
- Then **stock breaks out on chart** → go to full position
- **Breakout confirms market now seeing same thing I am seeing**

### Technical Analysis Exception: Extreme Oversold

**One exception where trade initiated because of charts:**

If stock extremely oversold — **RSI at 3-year low** — will take closer look

**Normally:** If stock that brutalized, means whatever is killing it is probably already in price

**RSI doesn't work as overbought indicator** — stocks can remain overbought for very long time

**But extremely oversold usually acute phenomenon** lasting only few weeks

**Process when RSI extremely oversold:**
1. Correct — RSI only useful in **oversold direction**
2. Look at fundamentals to see if whatever caused sharp selloff **already discounted by price**
3. If it is → then buy

## Gut Feel vs. Analysis

### Gut Feel Is Crucial

> "If something isn't acting right, it is an indication that you need to go back and recheck the fundamentals."

**Example: IBEX (Spanish stock index)**
- Thinking of substantially increasing short position
- Yesterday: several economic statistics released — **all awful**
- But market went up
- "So I scurried away"

**Did you cover your position?**
- No — didn't add to it
- Algorithmic funds clearly still in control
- "Would be insane for me to have a large position because I could get destroyed before market turns down"
- Have to wait before short Spain aggressively
- Gut feel: "Ugh, this is not acting right"
- But not covering because **fundamentally still think I am right**

## Advice and Worst Mistake

### Advice to Stock Investors

> "You have to be an expert in what you invest in. You need to understand why you are invested. If you don't understand why you are in a trade, you won't understand when it is the right time to sell, which means you will only sell when the price action scares you. Most of the time when price action scares you, it is a buy opportunity, not a sell indicator."

### Worst Trading Mistake of Career

