## Chapter 11: Tom Claugus - A Change of Plans

### Background and Career Path

**Thomas Claugus** planned financial security carefully:
- Chemical engineering degree + MBA from Harvard Business School
- Worked 2 years in chemical engineering, then Harvard, then back to **Rohm & Haas**
- Within 15 years: manager of European operations, on track to become CEO
- Loved his job and colleagues

**Parallel passion**: Avid stock investor from childhood
- Father invested in stocks; Claugus watched as child
- Discipline: lived on 1/3 of income, invested remainder
- Through strong performance and additional savings, stock account grew steadily
- Eventually earning more from stock account than executive position
- Decided to abandon successful career to become portfolio manager
- Most difficult decision he ever made; great personal angst

### Track Record

**17% average annual compounded net return** over 19-year period
- Personal account did even better: 33% gross compounding for 7 years prior to fund launch
- Combined 26-year track record: five losing years
  - Two very modest (3% or less)
  - 1991: -12%
  - 2008: -25%
  - 2011: -9%
- Each subsequent year's gain more than doubled the loss (excluding 2011, unknown at time)
- After dismal 2008, fund up 56% in 2009 (best year ever)

**Natural contrarian**: Lags badly when others make easy money, soars when others panic
- Mirror image investing evident in tech bubble finale (1999) and aftermath
- Small loss in 1999 (S&P 500 up 21%), then large gains during 2000-2002 bear market
- Exception: 2008 financial meltdown lost money with everyone else

**Even during strong equity years**, source of profits may be counterintuitive
- 1990s (fund launched 1993): 18% annual compounded return
- NOT by riding rising tide, but by being **net short throughout the period**
- Highly differentiated exposure levels attracted multifund portfolio managers
- GMT company currently manages $5.0 billion in onshore/offshore Bay Resource funds

### Early Stock Market Experience

**First interest age 9**: Father checked stock quotes daily; Claugus curious
- First stocks bought age 9 with paper route money
- Parents opened custodian account

**First picks**: Wheeling Pittsburgh Steel and McCrory (five and dime chain store)
- Both eventually bankrupt
- Made little on Wheeling Pittsburgh Steel
- Held McCrory into bankruptcy

**Father's influence**: Product of Depression, scared of poverty
- Somehow transferred insecurity to son
- From early age, Claugus wanted financial independence
- Freshman in college: created 30-year financial plan
- Calculated: saving 2/3 of income + earning 10% yearly = millionaire by age 53
- Chose chemical engineering: good at math/chemistry, engineering paid well
- Whole goal: make $12,000/year
- Almost switched to business several times during college

**Why didn't switch?**: Family science background
- Father: veterinarian; uncles: heart surgeon and engineer
- Science/engineering expected; business considered too easy
- Wasn't very good engineer but dedicated, worked extremely hard
- Father scared him about importance of doing well in school
- > "Tom, you are going to feel like you're going to jail. You can go out Friday night or Saturday night, but you can't go out both, or else you won't get ahead"

**Planned to get MBA** to combine chemical engineering + business degree = manager in chemical company

### Transition from Corporate Career to Portfolio Manager

**After first 2 years work**, went to Harvard Business School
- Got impression most classmates' families elated about Harvard acceptance
- Father not happy at all; Claugus not even sure he'd go
- Word got out at company; vice president took him to lunch
- > "This guy never even acknowledged my existence, and now he calls to take me out to lunch just because I was accepted. Maybe I should go to this place after all"

**Father's resistance**: Upset leaving $15,800 job to go back to school
- Father very tough guy; didn't start undergrad until mid-twenties
- Had to stay home, work family farm, take care of mother
- Measured almost everything in money terms
- Summers: helped father on farm, cutting timber
- Taught about trees; magnificent walnut tree "probably worth $3,000"

**Investment philosophy from day one**: Never wanted to depend on job for money
- Started investing from start
- Plan: live on 1/3 of income + 3% of net worth
- 3% net worth based on assumption of earning at least 10% yearly
- Effectively: plan to live on 1/3 of all income

**When incorporated shorting** (1986): Became concerned market overpriced
- Liked risk and market excitement
- Knew didn't have discipline to stay out
- Felt stocks too expensive, started shorting

**Started shorting early 1986**—almost year and a half before August 1987 peak
- Before market cracks, lower-quality stocks often zoom
- Summer 1987: Losing so much money playing tennis, had to call mother for loan to meet margin call
- Only one he could call; no way father would loan

**Stayed short all the way through crash**—just hung in

**October 19, 1987 crash**: As market crashing, started putting on longs to reduce net short
- Most memorable trade: buying **Mead Paper** at 32, filled at 27—market collapsing that quickly

**Didn't cover many shorts during freefall**: Most stocks short were low quality
- Didn't think need to cover quickly
- Started buying stocks really liked instead

**1987 profit**: First year made more money in market than job
- Eye-opener; every year after made more in market than job

### Decision to Leave Rohm & Haas

Year before leaving, would have said there "for the duration"
- Aspiration: CEO of Rohm & Haas
- Had been investing because liked risk taking, wanted financial independence
- Knew couldn't reach financial goals on salary alone
- Cruising along on good path; investments working
- Net worth reached $1.6 million
- Realization: > "3 percent of $1.6 million is $48,000; I could live on that"
- All of a sudden, economic necessity to keep working went away
- Until that point, constantly asked: *When are you going to do what you want to do? The answer would always be, Later*
- Did he really want to live in Philadelphia (Rohm & Haas location)? Not really
- Realization of economic freedom to sustain business 3-5 years turned him upside down
- **Spent a year in terrible turmoil**

**What turmoil?** Trying to decide what wanted to do
- Ultimately decided to manage money like managed own money
- Started hedge fund 1990 with $3 million (part his, rest friends/family)

**First time managing fund**: Went from regional director in Europe with everyone saying how smart he was
- To managing portfolio by himself out of home
- Felt very low sense of self-worth
- After 9 months: > "Claugus, you are a people person; you made a big mistake"

**What convinced mistake?** Loneliness—had spent 17 years at Rohm & Haas, missed friends

**Performance first 9 months**: Up in first 6 months, then started giving money back
- Still up a little when started questioning decision

**Once unsure**, afraid if continued and lost money:
- Would feel responsibility to make up difference to investors
- By reimbursing them, could lose all money saved during past 14 years

**Did managing differ from perception?** Yes
- Responsibility of other people's money really weighed
- 10-year horizon: can make good decisions and money
- 3-year horizon: still probably do well
- **But 3-month horizon: anything can happen**

**Why 3-month horizon?** Started doubting whether would continue

**Closed fund** at end of first year

**What prompted closing?** Talked to friends about how felt
- Rohm & Haas heard he was unhappy, offered him job
- Decided to take offer and close fund

**How felt closing fund**: Most startling thing
- Got offer letter from Rohm & Haas around Christmastime
- Never forget sinking feeling reading letter
- Offer: regional director of Asia based in Hong Kong
- Really had no desire to go to Asia

**Hadn't discussed job details before accepting?** No
- They'd basically said would bring him back into key job, possibly still in line for CEO
- Desperately needed someone good in Asia
- No one else qualified wanted to go
- Attitude: > "Tom wants to come back. Perfect. He has to earn his way back, and we'll send him to Asia. It will be well perceived by the organization"

**Resistance to going**: Walked out to put "for sale" sign in front of house, couldn't do it
- One son great gymnast, state champion
- Concern: Where would kids do athletics?
- Terrible feeling about it
- Called CEO: "Do you mind if I go to Hong Kong and check it out first?"
- CEO: "Sure, go to Hong Kong"

**At airport**, still not sure wanted to go
- Got out of line, then back in, then back out
- Finally got on plane

**Impression of Hong Kong**: Very crowded
- Offered to donate trampoline to school (laughs long at recollection)
- School said no room
- Wasn't wild about it, but decided would go anyway
- Tried to get psyched about going, just couldn't
- Needed to go back to check out again
- Replay of first visit
- Spent 5 months trying to get himself to go to Hong Kong
- **Became depressed, lost 45 pounds**

**Really didn't want the job**: First time decided to do something mentally conflicting with emotions
- Body stopped him in tracks
- Didn't realize it, but no way could go to Hong Kong
- Rohm & Haas had coach doing CEO assessments
- During this period, coach talking to him on phone
- She said: "Tom, I think you are clinically depressed. You need to see a psychiatrist. You need to do it right away"
- Found doctor who placed on antidepressants
- Finally went to Rohm & Haas—probably down to 135 pounds, looked like death
- Told them couldn't take Hong Kong job

**Came out of depression**: Very quickly after turned job down

**What did it?** That plus antidepressants
- Had friend who'd gone through depression
- Friend's advice: "Look Tom, here's what you have to do. I went through all this counseling, and all I can tell you is just get the drugs"
- After taking antidepressant about 2 weeks, cloud lifted, could see again

**Only episode of depression**

**Why became clinically depressed?** Trying to force self to go to Hong Kong when didn't want to
- But didn't know for sure why didn't want to

**Reason now?** Giving up on dream
- In heart, really wanted to be on own, hadn't taken it to completion

**Learn from experience?** Importance of having emotional side lined up with mental side for life-changing decisions

**After turning down Rohm & Haas**: Decided original plan to start hedge fund was what really wanted

**Started new hedge fund**: January 1993

**Year and a half wait**: After uncertainty first time, wanted to be sure of decision second time

**Concern about managing other people's money?** If 100% dedicated and lose money, can look in eye and say "I did my best"
- If not 100% engaged, not even sure want to be in business, managing other people's money very hard
- Once sure wanted to manage money, took away 80% of angst

**Why don't put up gates**: Had huge outflows 2008
- Didn't put up gates despite preferring to reduce investor withdrawals
- Would have been better off if didn't redeem in 2008
- People do things not in best interest
- Big difference between their making own decision vs. him telling them what's in best interest
- If investors want to redeem and he says can't because of gate, then loses their money = different feeling than losing money for investors who reached own decision to stay

**Second time working alone**: Enjoyed it

**What changed?** Just time; got used to working alone
- And loves investing

