### Early Career: Ben Graham and Net-Nets

- Started investing after reading **Ben Graham**, buying **net-nets** (stocks trading below liquidation value) before law school
- Master's thesis tested Graham's formula with **Richard Pzena** and **Bruce Newberg**
- Manually collected data from S&P stock guides (15% of universe) using University of Pennsylvania DEC10 computer
- Graham's decades-old formula still worked extremely well—portfolios beat indexes
- Study published in *Journal of Portfolio Management*, summer 1981
- Started fund with $250,000 from father's friends, returned 44% cumulatively over 2-3 years

### Options Trading at Bear Stearns

- First job: summer trading options at Bear Stearns after one year of law school
- Knew nothing about options—did **forward conversions** (riskless arbitrage earning 18-19% annualized)
- High interest rates made arbitrage attractive (~5-6% over risk-free rate)
- Trading was mechanical: run to other side of floor for printout, run back to execute
- By summer's end, realized no interest in trading options for a living

### Risk Arbitrage: Halcyon Investments (1981)

- December 1981: joined **Halcyon Investments** as analyst at $22,000 (half MBA rate)
- Startup risk arbitrage firm, three partners, only analyst
- **Merger arbitrage era**: "Wild West" with great inefficiencies, pedestrian year could return 60-80%
- Started right before major market bottom (13-year bear market)

### Philosophy: Attracted to Special Situations

- Never attracted to plain vanilla risk arbitrage's risk/reward structure
- **Ben Graham approach**: asymmetric returns on upside (can't lose much, large profit potential)
- **Risk arbitrage**: opposite structure—make $1-2 if merger succeeds, risk $10-20 if it breaks
- Drawn to **periphery of risk arbitrage**: hostile deals, paper securities instead of cash, **special situations**
- Liked **complicated situations** typical Wall Street analysts wouldn't evaluate
- "If there was a 400-page document to read, I was attracted to analyzing the deal because I knew most other people wouldn't read it"

### Marriott Spinoff Trade (early 1990s)

- **Marriott** caught in real estate downturn, stuck owning underlying hotels
- Spun off hotels and debt into **Host Marriott**, kept good business as **Marriott International**
- Hotel management was "Buffett type of business" being relieved of all debt
- **Toxic waste**: Host Marriott was heavily leveraged, out-of-favor, unwanted

**Why it was attractive:**
- Clearly unwanted by anyone who could read newspaper or balance sheet
- Institutions would likely sell—spinoff was 10-15% of original company, too small for them
- Different business (hotel ownership vs. management)
- Lack of new buying interest = likely undervaluation

**Analysis:**
- Insiders had large stake in spinoff
- Mastermind of spinoff was running the "bad business"—wouldn't choose it if truly bad
- Marriott family retaining 25% ownership in Host Marriott
- **Tremendous leverage**: expected to trade $3-5/share with debt of $20-25
- Share price of $5 with $25 debt = assets worth ~$30
- 15% increase in asset value would nearly double stock value
- Leverage works both ways, but upside potential was lopsided vs. downside (stock can't go below zero)
- Large insider ownership suggested deal wouldn't be structured to fail
- Marriott International extending $600 million line of credit to Host Marriott

**Outcome:** As expected, institutions dumped shares at low price. Stock nearly tripled in four months.

### Wells Fargo LEAPS Trade (early 1990s)

- **Wells Fargo** under pressure from high concentration of California commercial real estate loans during deep recession
- Possibility (unlikely) real estate downturn could wipe out all equity before investors benefit from long-term fee generation
- Stock at $80, depressed by prevailing concerns
- **Binary situation**: go down $80 if business fails, up $80 if it survives
- Bought **LEAPS** with 2+ years to expiration instead of stock
- Transformed 1:1 risk/reward into **1:5 risk/reward**
- If bank survived, stock should double; would make 5x on options vs. losing only cost of options if failed
- Assessed odds much better than 50/50 for survival
- Stock more than doubled before options expired

### Transition to Systematic Value (1995-2005)

- Continued special situations approach for ~10 years after returning investor money in 1995
- Gradual transition to systematic value approach starting 2003

**Why the change:**
- Always wanted to test principles used in teaching and managing money
- 2003: hired **Rob Goldstein** and skilled computer programmer
- Backtested key measures for evaluating companies
- First metric tested: **Ben Graham's principle of buying cheap**

### Defining "Cheap": Earnings Yield

- Used **earnings yield**: ratio of EBIT (earnings before interest and taxes) to **enterprise value**
- **Enterprise value** = market value of equity + net interest-bearing debt
- Superior to P/E or E/P ratios for several reasons

**Why EBIT/EV vs. P/E:**
- Accounts for debt financing used to generate operating earnings
- Allows comparison of companies with different debt levels and tax rates on equal footing
- Example: office building with $800k mortgage, $200k equity = $200k equity price but $1M enterprise value
- EBIT of $100k → EBIT/EV = 10% vs. misleading equity calculations
- P/E and E/P greatly influenced by debt levels and tax rates; **EBIT/EV is not**

### Defining "Good Business": Return on Tangible Capital

- **Warren Buffett's twist**: nice to buy cheap businesses, but better to buy a **good business cheap**
- Buffett metric: **return on tangible capital**
- Example: **Jason's Gum Shop** costs $400k to set up, throws off $200k profit = 50% return on capital
- **Just Broccoli** costs $400k, throws off $10k profit = 2.5% return on capital
- Question: *How efficiently does it turn its fixed assets and working capital into profits?*
- **Return on tangible capital** = EBIT / (net working capital + net fixed assets)

**Why tangible capital:**
- Company must fund receivables and inventory (working capital needed)
- Doesn't have to fund payables (interest-free loan)
- Short-term interest-bearing debt excluded from current liabilities
- Must also fund purchase of fixed assets (real estate, plant, equipment)
- Depreciated net cost of fixed assets added to net working capital = tangible capital employed

### The Magic Formula

- Combined two rankings: earnings yield + return on capital
- Equally weighted by adding rankings
- Example: company ranked #1 on earnings yield, #250 on return on capital = combined rank 251
- "We weren't looking for the cheapest companies, and we weren't looking for the best companies. We were looking for the best combination of cheap and good companies."

**Backtest results (23 years from 1988):**
- Top 30 names from 1,000 largest cap stocks **approximately doubled** S&P 500 return
- 19.7% vs. 9.5% annually
- 2,500 largest companies would have had even larger outperformance
- **2000-2009**: averaged 13.5% annual return while S&P 500 down nearly 1% annually

**Decile analysis:**
- Divided rankings into 10 deciles (250 stocks each)
- Held for one year, repeated monthly, stepping through time over 23 years
- **Perfect ordering**: Decile 1 beat 2, 2 beat 3, 3 beat 4, all the way down
- Decile 1: averaged 15%+ per year
- Decile 10 (bad businesses at expensive prices): lost average of 0.2% per year
- Huge spread between Decile 1 and Decile 10

### Why Not Long Decile 1 / Short Decile 10?

> "Sometime in the year 2000, your shorts would have gone up so much more than your longs that you would have lost 100 percent of your money."

- Value investing doesn't always work
- Market doesn't always agree over short term (can be 2-3 years)
- **Formula forces buying out-of-favor companies** that may underperform 2-3 years
- Most people abandon strategy after 1-2 years of underperformance, switching to recent winners
- Difficult to follow value approach without **sufficient confidence**
- Must understand core principle: buying above-average companies at below-average prices
- Only way to stick with non-working strategy is **understanding what you are doing**

### Current Implementation: Refined Systematic Approach

- Now have 10 analysts analyzing income statements, balance sheets, cash flow statements
- Build real cash flow, real assets, real liabilities based on company analysis
- Built proprietary database for 4,000+ U.S. and foreign stocks
- Still looking backward (no forward-looking estimates)
- More complex analysis helpful for diversified portfolios, but 20-30 stocks following either method works well

### Evolution: From Concentrated to Diversified

- Original fund and personal account: 6-8 main positions, superior returns with high concentration
- With larger capital, prefers **compounding at good return without greater volatility**
- Current systematic approach: can construct long/short portfolios with hundreds of names
- Long side: hundreds of names; short side: hundreds of names
- Can earn 15-20% annually, compounding with much less volatility
- Evolved process, not changed principles—**systematized same principles** always used
- Different approaches for different contexts; **one is not better than the other**
- Main goal: **reduce volatility**

> "People don't fully appreciate the importance of not losing money. Negative compounding is very difficult to overcome. If you lose 50 percent of your money, you have to make 100 percent to recover the loss."

- More diversified long/short portfolio = smoother ride, better compounding opportunity
- Research showed approach worked better than expected, could apply to hundreds of holdings
- Led to launching several long/short funds and index-like diversification funds

### Risk Management in Long/Short

- Rob Goldstein and interviewer directly manage risk
- Team of six smart technology people (no financial background)
- Purposely picked people without financial background—wanted to be portfolio managers themselves
- Manage betas on long and short side
- Limit concentration in any specific industry group
- Limit exposure in any single stock
- Widely diversified portfolio: largest long position ~0.6% equity, largest short even smaller

### Index Innovation: Fundamentally Weighted Indexes

**Problem with market-cap weighted indexes:**
- 70% of mutual fund managers underperform S&P 500 due to fees
- No correlation between past performance (3, 5, 10 years) and future performance
- Obvious conclusion: go with index fund (lower cost, tax efficient)
- **BUT**: market-cap weighted indexes are very inefficient
- Higher stock price → larger percentage of index → **automatically own too much overpriced, too few bargain-priced**
- Equal weighted indexes also have valuation errors, but random vs. systematic

**Equal weighting advantage:**
- Equal weighting beat market-cap weighting by ~2% per year over past 40 years
- **Problem**: stock #500 much smaller than stock #1; equal weighting would distort prices
- More transaction costs maintaining equal weighted index

**Solution: RAFI FTSE index (Rob Arnott):**
- Weights companies based on size of **sales, book value, cash flow, and dividends** (not market capitalization)
- Weighting factors correlated to company market cap, so larger companies still account for larger percentage
- Since price not involved, errors are random (like equal weighted), not systematic
- Index performs ~2% better than capitalization weighted indexes

### Fundamentally Weighted Index Performance

- Created index that allocated more money to cheaper stocks
- Over past 20 years: would have beaten S&P 500 by average of **7% per year** with same beta and volatility
- Also created more select funds: ~100 cheapest stocks weighted by cheapness

**Recent divergent performance:**
- First six months of year: **Value Select fund** (U.S. equities) was #1 in category out of 1,300 funds
- **Select International fund** was single worst fund in category out of 400 funds
- Both following exact same strategy in different markets

**Implication:**
- Value Select (best): beat market by only 5%
- Select International (worst): underperformed market by only 5%
- Narrow spread suggests **no one was really picking stocks**—almost everyone index hugging

### Small Cap Opportunity

- Doesn't believe in "small cap anomaly" within Russell 3000
- **Does** think important to look in small-cap universe
- **Lesser-followed companies more likely to be misvalued**
- Misvaluations can be both over and under, no directional bias on average
- Small-cap sector may be particularly fertile ground for finding undervalued stocks (less followed)

### Value Investors Club

**Origin (1999):**
- Found one of best ideas in portfolio
- Partner **John Petry** found Yahoo message board posting with precisely same analysis
- Reaction: *"Well, apparently, there is intelligent life out there."*
- Decided to create group for sharing ideas

**Membership:**
- Prequalifying requirement: submit investment write-up on specific company that would receive A+ grade in Columbia class
- Only 2-3 students per year achieved this grade
- Set bar very high
- Limit: 250 members

**Judging and operation:**
- Originally interviewer and **John Petry** (co-founder) judged submissions
- Now board of John Petry and close managers (anonymous to applicants)

**Requirements:**
- No membership fees
- Each member must submit two idea write-ups per year
- Must assign rating to 20 other ideas
- If willing to share best ideas, can stay; if not, asked to leave

**Public access:**
- For teaching and attracting talent: allow nonmembers access to posted ideas with 90-day lag (45-day with registration)
- Since ideas are value-based, many still timely after lags

**Success:**
- Good source of ideas over time
- Met incredibly talented people
- Helped some start their own funds
- Members are people passionate about investing
- Most chose smaller amounts and higher returns rather than building big business
- About half of 250 members are professional managers

### Three Biggest Investor Mistakes

1. **Succumbing to emotions** - making investment decisions based on emotional response to price action, news, or media
2. **Investing without knowledge** - can't value a company without ability to properly value (probably only 1-2% of investors can)
3. **Placing too much weight on recent past performance of managers**

### Natural Experiment: Magic Formula Website

- After writing *The Little Book That Beats the Market*, investors asked for help executing strategy
- Created website **magicformulainvesting.com** with **Blake Darcy** (DLJ Direct founder)
- Benevolent brokerage: pick own stocks from preselected "value" list
- Encouraged to pick 20-30 stocks for diversification vs. few stocks
- Blake added checkbox: option to have portfolio managed vs. picking stocks themselves
- **Less than 10%** chose to do it themselves; **over 90%** checked box for management

**Results tracked over first two years:**
- Self-managed accounts **underperformed professionally managed accounts by over 25%**
- Effectively created control group experiment
- Same principles, exact same stock list, but letting investors make own decisions destroyed outperformance

**Why self-managed did worse:**
- Took exposure down when market fell
- Tended to sell individual stocks or portfolios as whole when underperformed
- Did much worse than random in selecting stocks from prescreened list
- By avoiding particularly painful stocks, missed some of biggest winners

### Worst Mistake: Key3Media (Ziff-Davis Spinoff)

- **Key3Media**: great return on tangible capital, great operating leverage
- Trade show company running COMDEX (largest technology trade show)
- Rented Las Vegas space at $2/sq ft, re-rented at $62
- Impending spinoff (special situation allowing long exposure)
- Bought at $3/share pre-spinoff (very cheap)
- Several months later IPO'd at $6/share (quick double)
- Within few more months, stock price doubled from IPO level
- Single stock quadrupled from entry, grew to ~40% of portfolio

**The mistake:**
- Business started to falter
- **Worst loss**: company made large acquisition two days before 9/11
- After 9/11, people stopped traveling
- Operating leverage reversed: profits went down almost dollar for dollar with revenue decline
- Had leveraged up to make acquisition
- By time completely liquidated position, lost back all profits "and then some"

**Lessons:**
> "Stuff happens. Don't fall in love with any position. Always keep a large margin of safety, even if you're playing with house money."

- Stock was less attractive value after quadrupling
- Should have taken some profits
- **Operating leverage works both ways** (quote from **Howard Marks**: "Experience is what you got when you didn't get what you wanted")

### Measuring Risk

- As value investor, looks at **risk of loss over the long term**
- Given margin of safety, how much can lose if hold stock 2-3 years?
- Doesn't look at stock's volatility in last three months
- "I think volatility is so widely used as a risk metric simply because it is easy to measure, not because it is a good gauge of risk of permanent loss of capital."
- **Downside volatility**: one aspect of risk, not necessarily most important
- **Upside volatility**: not much of a risk unless you are short

### Teaching at Columbia

- Teaches at Columbia Business School
- First four years: Security Analysis course
- Past 12 years: **Value and Special Situation Investing**
- Courses not that different

**What he teaches (following Buffett):**
1. **How to value a business**
2. **How to think about stock prices**

**First lecture message:**
- Although students are smart, and other business school students are smart, **most MBAs involved in markets will fail**
- Can't be intelligence that defines success
- Difference: **how they think about the market**
- Need methodology to cut through daily bombardment: price movements, explanations, macro events
- All comes back to how **Graham looked at the market**
- Short term: prices fluctuate due to emotion
- Long term: prices come back to value
- **Value investing**: figuring out what business is worth and paying a lot less

**Time horizon promise:**
> "I promise my students that if they do good valuation work, the market will agree with them; I just don't tell them when. It could be a few weeks, a few months, or even a few years. But generally, if you have done good valuation work, 98 percent of the time, two or three years is enough time for the market to agree with you."

- Very powerful concept—gives patience
- Good valuation work + wide margin of safety + confidence → eventually will do quite well

**For difficult-to-value companies:**
- If in competitive industry, technology causing major changes, new products coming, or other circumstances making future earnings hard to estimate → **skip that company**
- Find company they can analyze
- **"There are no called strikes on Wall Street."** (Warren Buffett)
- Can watch as many pitches as you want, only swing when everything sets up right

**Opportunity set consideration:**
- Consider not only what opportunity set is right now, but **opportunities may be forgoing later** by investing now
- If opportunity set not great now, maybe wait 6-12 months before becoming fully invested
- Don't invest all capital based on current opportunity set—might not have money for better future opportunities
- Might have to sell current holdings at lower price to free up money
- **Minimum bogie**: at least 6% return even if interest rates near zero
- Must beat 6% by measurable amount (assumption is 6% is risk-free)
- Wouldn't take 8% unless high confidence it will grow over time
- Need **"margin of safety"** (Graham)
- Compare normalized earnings to risk-free rate (currently 6%)
- Opportunity set: not only current choices but what choices might be at some future time

### Experience with Investors

**Early fund of funds investor (1988):**
- Gotham Capital sending quarterly letters
- Fund of funds required monthly numbers
- First month: up 1.1% (interviewer thought pretty good)
- Call from fund of funds head: "You know, we have a lot of investments with firms like yours, and, on average, they were up 1.2 percent last month. To what do you attribute your underperformance?"

**Institutional pressure for short-term performance:**
- Sits on multibillion-dollar investment boards
- Direct experience: after 4-5 quarters, one manager outperforms, another underperforms
- Natural response: "One guy knows what he's doing, and the other guy doesn't."
- Statistics demonstrate **money follows performance**—most allocators chase who did well recently
- Hard to resist because getting data constantly, have fiduciary responsibility to do good job
- World more institutionalized over last 25 years
- More number crunching, short-term performance monitoring
- **Time horizons have continually shortened**

**Implications:**
- **Advantage of longer-term investment horizon has increased**
- With databases, computing power, Internet, smart people in markets—factors that have done well over 20 years would tend to degrade over time
- **BUT**: valuation metrics they use are longer term, require willingness to wait
- Have gotten stronger, not weaker
- **Reason**: institutionalization shortened time horizons, reduced window for managers to outperform
- Most managers can't wait two years for investment to work
- Have to perform now
- Institutional and individual clients demand it through money flows
- Companies not expected to do well in next 1-2 years, or subject to near-term uncertainty, are **systematically underpriced**
- Even if manager knows should look longer term, investors pressure him for near-term performance

**Money chasing past performance:**
- Statistics: money chases guy who did well last year, leaves guy who didn't
- Subsequent performance actually worse for guy who did well last year
- Looking at past 3-, 5-, 10-year returns: **no correlation** between those who did well in prior periods and those who do well in subsequent 3, 5, 10 years
- Returns are what allocators normally rely on to make decisions
- Allocators typically don't know thought process behind each investment decision
- Only see results
- **Past results very misleading** in terms of who will do better in future

**Performance persistence study (2000-2009):**
- 97% of top quartile managers spent at least three years in bottom half
- 79% of top quartile managers spent at least three years in bottom quartile
- Nearly half spent at least three years in bottom decile
- Investors didn't stick with bottom quartile/decile managers
- **Yet those were the managers that ended up with the best performance**

### Shortened Time Horizons Create Opportunity

- Availability of data, computing power, Internet, smart people should degrade factors that worked historically
- **Instead**: valuation metrics have gotten stronger
- Institutionalization reduced time managers have to outperform
- Most can't wait for investments to work
- Must perform now through client money flow demands
- Creates systematic underpricing of companies not expected to do well near-term or facing near-term uncertainty
- Manager knows should look longer term, but investors pressure for near-term performance

**Quote about capital flows:**
> "A fat wallet is the enemy of good investment returns." — Warren Buffett

- Very difficult to have a lot of great ideas
- If investors keep piling in money, managers forced to do something with it
- May do things differently than when they had less money

**Recent study findings:**
- 97% of top managers for decade spent at least three years in bottom half
- 79% spent at least three years in bottom quartile
- Nearly 50% spent at least three years in bottom decile
- Investors didn't stick with them
- Those managers ended up with best performance

