## Continuation: Joel Greenblatt - Interview & Columbia Class

### Manager Selection Paradox

- Best-performing mutual fund of the decade: +18% annually, but average investor lost 8%
- Timing of investor flows destroys returns: pile in after good performance, redeem after underperformance
- **Capital allocators should focus on process, not returns**—returns have no predictive value
- Picking a good manager is as difficult as picking good stocks

### Periodic Underperformance Is Natural

- To beat the market, must do something different from the market
- Doing something different inevitably means significant underperformance at times
- Example: **Value investing** can underperform badly when markets respond to emotion and momentum

### Education Reform Journey

**Initial Philanthropy**
- Backed seventh-grade class in high-needs Long Island community
- Many kids were 4-5 grades behind—charity helped after school, but kids wasted most of school day
- Recognized need to intervene earlier: kindergarten or first grade

**Success for All Program**
- Connected with **Dr. Robert Slavin** (Johns Hopkins)—top education researcher
- **Success for All**: reading and math program for K-1
- Only achieved 50-60% grade-level results despite significant impact
- Greenblatt asked: "Would more money help?" Slavin: "Of course, if spent right."

**Charter School Path**
- Tried to fund program in same Long Island school—superintendent refused
- Eventually found Queens school willing to implement K-5 program
- Second year: won award for most improved school in New York State
- Cost: **$1,000/year per child**

**Scaling Through Charter Schools**
- Met **Joel Klein** (NYC Department of Education Chancellor) due to bureaucracy challenges
- Klein suggested charter schools for hiring flexibility
- 2006: **John Petry** and Greenblatt started single charter school as prototype
- Hired **Eva Moskowitz** to run program—designed for replication
- Eva has opened nine charter schools, four more scheduled next year

### Charter School Results

**Performance**
- New York law requires charter schools start small, add one grade per year
- Unions helped pass law to handicap charter growth
- Only four schools reached testing grades (3-8) so far
- **All four tested schools beat Scarsdale, Great Neck, and all top districts in state**
- All four schools located in **Harlem**

**Demand**
- Nine kids applying for every spot (lottery-based admission)

**Documentaries**
- **Harlem Success** profiled in *Waiting for Superman*
- Another documentary: *The Lottery* focused solely on Harlem Success

### Education Reform Philosophy

**Scale and Impact**
- K-12 education is **$600 billion business**—philanthropy cannot be the answer
- Philanthropy's role: show the way
- Charter schools are public schools, independently run
- Same kids, same parents as publicly run schools—lottery-based selection
- Less money per student than public schools
- **Bottom line**: same kids, same parents, less money—yet dramatically better results

**Systemic Change**
- Goal: demonstrate what works, then share intellectual property
- Steal liberally from successful charter schools
- Not about average charter performance—about finding models that work and scaling them
- "Like capitalism in general. You want to find winners and reproduce those."

### Political Landscape

**Teacher Union Opposition**
- Unions protest every new school opening—don't want competition
- Union plan: "kill us with 1,000 cuts"—oppose at every step
- If charter network survives 10 years and scales to 30-40 schools, could transform discussion

**Presidential Support**
- Greenblatt disagrees with **President Obama** on economic issues
- But Obama has been "very progressive on education issue"
- Democrats generally in pocket of teachers unions
- Obama went against party stance, embraced reform—"give him credit"
- **Race to the Top** program: incentivized states to adopt pro-reform policies for charter schools

### Columbia Business School Class Visit

**Q&A Format**
- Greenblatt answered questions as **Warren Buffett** would
- Students continually confused whether Greenblatt was answering as Buffett or himself
- Philosophy so closely aligned that distinction often didn't matter

**Teaching His Son to Invest**
- Oldest son (college senior) studying to be opera singer
- "Maybe I should learn about investing—going to be starving for 5-6 years"
- Started teaching in June
- Son said: "Stock prices have been crazy since then. Everything you told me I would experience happened during first five months watching market."
- Example stock: went $16 → $9 → $18 → $16 again
- Business didn't change at all during period, yet price changed significantly
- > "There are too many people looking at stocks; there are no more opportunities." There are plenty of opportunities.

**Key Investment Principles**
- You're setting yourself up for failure if you invest differently than you want to in order to please investors
- Manage your own account if you can—nothing like actually doing it, learning what it's like to lose money and experience emotions
- > "Time is the enemy of the poor business and the friend of the great business." —Buffett
- Looking at return on capital keeps you out of value traps
- **Computer Associates story** (**Rich Pzena**): Called top 12 customers, all hated the company, product, service, everything. Asked if competitor offered software/services free, would they switch? All 12: "Are you crazy? We can't switch. Can't close business for a few days to switch to competitor."
  - **Sticky business** example—customers can't leave despite hating everything

### Three Critical Lessons About Value Investing

1. **Value investing works**
2. **Value investing doesn't work all the time**
3. **Item 2 is one of the reasons why Item 1 is true**

### Time Arbitrage and Investor Behavior

**The Value Edge**
- Investing in good businesses at cheap prices (Buffett's approach) outperforms long-term
- Value edge doesn't disappear because underperformance periods (few years) are long and severe enough to discourage investors
- Shortening of investor time horizons in tolerating subpar performance is critical problem
- Institutions increasingly likely to redeem from managers after 1-2 years of below-average performance
- Risk of losing substantial assets means managers who stick to value approach risk career damage
- **Inability of investors and managers to invest with long-term horizon creates opportunity for *time arbitrage***—edge that requires commitment to long-term holding periods

### Efficient Market Hypothesis Critique

**Greenblatt's View**
- EMH provides inaccurate model of how market really works
- Market will eventually trade to fair value consistent with EMH
- **But in interim (sometimes years), stocks can deviate substantially from fair value**
- More appropriate model: prices trade around fair value, but broad deviations occur due to wide swings in investor emotions

**Mr. Market Metaphor**
- Invokes **Benjamin Graham's** famous metaphor from *The Little Book That Beats the Market*
- **Mr. Market**: hypothetical business partner, subject to erratic moods
- Willing to sell shares to you or buy shares from you based on mood

> Sometimes Mr. Market is in such a good mood that he names a price that is much higher than the true worth of the business. On such days, it probably would make sense for you to sell Mr. Market your share of the business. On other days, he is in such a poor mood that he names a very low price for the business. On those days, you may want to take advantage of Mr. Market's crazy offer to sell you shares at such a low price and to buy Mr. Market's share of the business.

- Don't have to trade—wait for right opportunity and right time
- Referencing Buffett: > "There are no called strikes on Wall Street." "You can watch as many pitches as you want, and only swing when everything sets up your way."

### Manager Selection Mistakes

**Past Performance Is Not Predictive**
- Biggest mistake: using past performance as guide for selecting managers
- Empirical evidence shows no meaningful correlation between past and future manager performance rankings
- Should select managers based on investment **process** rather than returns

**Index Funds vs. Mutual Funds**
- Since past performance not predictive, stock indexes better investment than mutual funds on average
- Lower fees and more tax-efficient structure
- But most popular stock indexes are structurally flawed

**Capitalization-Weighted Index Flaws**
- SP500 and Russell indexes are **cap-weighted**
- More overvalued a stock becomes, greater allocation
- More undervalued, lower allocation—**exact reverse** of what would be desirable
- **Equal-weighted indexes** avoid this problem, add ~2% per year vs. cap-weighted indexes

**Value-Weighted Indexes**
- Not to be confused with cap-weighted value index
- Can add significant additional improvement
- May provide most attractive long-only equity investment alternative

### Wells Fargo Options Trade

**Binary Outcome Scenario**
- Uncertainty whether Wells Fargo would survive severe real estate downturn
- If survived, fee income suggested far higher price
- Binary outlook: greater-than-normal chance of either large gain or large loss
- **Long-term long options position**: almost as much upside potential on large move, but limited risk
- Particularly attractive trade

**Broader Lesson**
- Options primarily priced off mathematical models that don't account for specific fundamentals
- If you can identify situation where fundamentals suggest large move up, down, or either direction more likely than normal, options may provide very attractive risk/reward trade

### Asset Size and Performance

**Gotham Capital Restraint**
- Not a lesson relevant to most investors, but critical to managers
- Guard against letting assets grow to point where size impedes performance
- Greenblatt's spectacular track record in first 10 years could have easily grown fund by multiples, collecting hefty management fees
- **Instead: returned all assets to investors** to keep money under management (his own and partners') small enough not to interfere with strategy execution or impede performance

---

## Conclusion: 40 Market Wizard Lessons

### 1. There Is No Holy Grail in Trading

- No single solution to defining market behavior
- Solutions that exist are continually changing
- Range of methods used by interviewed traders (some polar opposites) testament to diversity of possible approaches
- Multitude of ways to be successful, albeit all hard to find and achieve

### 2. Find a Trading Method That Fits Your Personality

- Must find methodology that fits own beliefs and talents
- Sound methodology successful for one trader can be poor fit and losing strategy for another
- **O'Shea quote**:

> If I try to teach you what I do, you will fail because you are not me. If you hang around me, you may pick up some good habits. But there are a lot of things you will want to do differently. A good friend of mine, who sat next to me for several years, is now managing lots of money at another hedge fund and doing very well. But he is not the same as me. What he learned was not to become me. He became something else. He became him.

### 3. Trade Within Your Comfort Zone

- If position too large, trader prone to exit good trades on inconsequential corrections because fear dominates decision
- **Clark**: "trade within your emotional capacity"
- **Vidich**: "Limit your size in any position so that fear does not become the prevailing instinct guiding your judgment"
- Smaller net exposure may yield better returns, *even if market ultimately moves in favorable direction*
- **Taylor example**: came into 2008 with large net long in high beta stocks in risky market. Uncomfortable with exposure level, sharply reduced positions early January. When market plunged later in month, well positioned to increase long exposure. Had remained heavily net long, might have been forced to sell into weakness to reduce risk, missing subsequent rebound.

### 4. Flexibility Is an Essential Quality for Trading Success

- Highly skilled traders not only liquidate positions if they believe they made mistake, but will actually reverse those positions
- **O'Shea April 2008**: pessimistic about financial outlook, but market behavior told him he was wrong. Formulated alternative hypothesis—Asia-led economic recovery. Flexibility in recognizing original premise wrong and ability to reverse turned potentially disastrous year into winning one.
- **Mai's best 2011 trade**: shorting dry bulk shippers—ironically originated with premise these represented buying opportunity. When research showed not only wrong, but exactly backward, reversed original trading plan.
- **Clark**: good traders can change minds in an instant. Absolutely convinced market going higher one moment, just as convinced going lower the next.

### 5. The Need to Adapt

- Nice to believe if you find working methodology and have discipline to apply consistently, then trading success assured
- **Reality**: Markets change, strategies that work may eventually deteriorate
- Must be vigilant to possibility once reliable approach may lose efficacy or become losing strategy
- **Thorp**: maintained strong return/risk of statistical arbitrage by continually adapting. By third iteration, original system significantly degraded.
- **Platt** (BlueCrest): systematic approaches must continually be revised or degrade. Describes as "research war."
- **Balodimas**: had to adapt less aggressive posture positioning against ongoing trends once realized growing hedge fund participation resulting in smoother, more prolonged market trends. Had he not responded, previous successful approach would likely have led to large losses.

### 6. Don't Confuse Winning and Losing Trades with Good and Bad Trades

- Good trade can lose money, bad trade can make money
- Even best trading processes lose certain percentage of time
- No way of knowing a priori which individual trade will make money
- As long as trade adhered to process with positive edge, it's good trade, regardless of win or loss
- If similar trades repeated multiple times, will come out ahead
- Conversely, trade taken as gamble is bad trade regardless of whether wins or loses—over time such trades will lose money

### 7. Do More of What Works and Less of What Doesn't

- Core advice from **Clark** may sound obvious, but many traders violate principle
- Quite common for trader to be good at one type of trade, but degrade performance by engaging in trades without clear edge
- Traders need to figure out what they're best at and focus attention on those types of trades

### 8. If You Are Out of Sync with the Markets, Trying Harder Won't Help

- When trading going badly, trying harder often makes matters worse
- If in losing streak, best action may be to step away from markets
- **Clark**: best way to handle losing streak is liquidate everything and take vacation
- Physical break can interrupt downward spiral and loss of confidence during losing periods
- When trading resumed, size should be kept small until confidence regained

### 9. The Road to Success Is Paved with Mistakes

- **Dalio**: learning from mistakes essential to improvement and ultimate success
- Each mistake, if recognized and acted on, provides opportunity for improving trading approach
- Most traders benefit by writing down: (1) each mistake, (2) implied lesson, (3) intended change in trading process
- Trading log can be periodically reviewed for reinforcement
- Trading mistakes cannot be avoided, but repeating same mistakes can be—doing so often difference between success and failure

### 10. Wait for High-Conviction Trades

- Patience to wait for high expected value trades greatly enhances return/risk of individual trades
- **Mai**: perfectly content to stay on sidelines and do absolutely nothing until trade opportunity meets guidelines
- **Greenblatt**: for longer-term investors, placing suboptimal positions may tie up capital that could be applied to more attractive opportunities arising in future or require liquidating such positions at loss to free up capital

### 11. Trade Because of Perceived Opportunity, Not Out of Desire to Make Money

- **Benedict** end of 2010: took marginal trades out of desire to reach minimum profit target for year
- Trades resulted in net losses, ended even further from intended target
- Trading to make money always bad idea
- Traders should only take trade when market provides opportunity as defined by their own individual strategy

### 12. The Importance of Doing Nothing

- For some traders, discipline and patience to do nothing when environment unfavorable or opportunities lacking is crucial element
- **Daly**: achieved cumulative gross returns exceeding 800% during 12-year period when broad equity markets essentially flat
- Accomplished by having discipline to remain largely in cash during negative environments, allowing him to sidestep large drawdowns during two major bear markets
- **Lesson**: if conditions not right, or return/risk not sufficiently favorable, don't do anything
- Beware of taking dubious trades out of impatience

### 13. How a Trade Is Implemented Can Be More Important Than the Trade Itself

- **O'Shea example**: trading assumption that bubble had burst in equities following initial break from March 2000 peak
- Did not consider short positions in Nasdaq because of danger of treacherous bear market rallies
- Instead, implemented via long bond position—reasoning bear market in equities implied most assets would recede from inflated levels, leading to economic slowdown and lower interest rates
- Even though stock market went much lower, if O'Shea had implemented via short stock index position, high likelihood stopped out by 40% rebound in Nasdaq during summer 2000
- Long bond position witnessed fairly smooth uptrend
- **Trade highly successful not because underlying premise correct, but rather because of way trade was implemented**
- If gone short stock index instead, would have been correct on call, but most likely lost money by being stopped out during steep bear market rally in equities

### 14. Trading Around a Position Can Be Beneficial

- Most traders view trades as two-step process: decision when to enter and decision when to exit
- May be better to view trading as dynamic rather than static process between entry and exit points
- **Basic idea**: as trade moves in intended direction, position exposure gradually reduced. Larger the move and closer to target objective, more position reduced.
- After reducing exposure, position reinstated on market correction
- Anytime market retraced to correction reentry point, net profit would be generated even if otherwise wouldn't have been realized
- Choppier the market, more excess profits trading around position will generate
- Even trade where market fails to move in intended direction on balance could still be profitable via gains from lightening position on favorable trend moves and reinstating liquidated portions on corrections
- Reduces chances of being knocked out of favorable position on correction—if position already reduced, correction will have less impact and may even be desired to reinstate liquidated portion
- **Only negative outcome**: if market keeps going in intended direction without ever retracing to correction reentry levels—but this simply means original trade profitable, just total profits smaller
- **In nutshell**: trading around position will generate extra profits and increase chances of staying with good trades at expense of sometimes giving up portion of profits on trades that move smoothly in intended direction
- **Balodimas**: trading around position is critical ingredient in overall trading success. Not infrequently, allows him to be profitable on trades where he's wrong.

### 15. Position Size Can Be More Important Than the Entry Price

- Too many traders focus only on entry price and pay insufficient attention to size of position
- Trading too large can result in good trades being liquidated at loss because of fear
- Trading larger than normal when profit potential appears much greater than risk is key way many Market Wizards achieve superior returns
- Trading smaller, or not at all, for lower probability trades and larger for higher probability trades can even transform losing strategy into winning one
- **Thorp example**: by varying bet size based on perceived probabilities, was able to transform negative edge in Blackjack into positive edge
- Analogous principle applies to trading strategy where possible to identify higher and lower probability trades

### 16. Determining the Trade Size

- **Optimal trade size**: mathematically precise answer is **Kelly criterion** (Chapter 6)
- Will provide higher cumulative return over long run than any other strategy for determining trade size
- **Problem**: Kelly criterion assumes probability of winning and ratio of amount won to amount lost per wager are precisely known
- Although assumption valid for games of chance, in trading probability of winning is unknown and at best can only be estimated
- If win/loss probabilities can be reasonably estimated, Kelly criterion can provide starting point
- **Thorp recommendation**: trade only **half the Kelly amount** because:
  - Penalty for overestimating correct trade size is severe
  - Most people would find volatility implied by full Kelly amount too high for comfort level
- If win/loss probabilities can't be reasonably estimated, Kelly criterion can't be used

### 17. Vary Market Exposure Based on Opportunities

- Exposure levels and even direction should vary based on opportunities and perceived relative value
- **Claugus example**: depending on whether stock prices appear cheaply or expensively priced, varies net exposure range from 110% long to 70% short
- Varying exposure based on opportunity can lead to significantly improved performance results

### 18. Seek an Asymmetric Return/Risk Profile

- **Mai**: structures trades to be *right skewed*—maximum loss limited, but upside open-ended
- Common way: selective buyer of options when perceived greater-than-normal probability of large price move
- **O'Shea**: structures almost all trades to be right skewed. Uses long options, credit default swap (CDS) protection, long T-bill/short Eurodollar (TED) spreads—all trades where maximum loss constrained
- **Platt**: achieves right-skewed asymmetry at portfolio level through risk control process
  - Strictly limits each trader's maximum loss from starting allocation each year
  - Doesn't raise risk cutoff level if trader generates profits during year
  - Portfolio maximum loss tightly curtailed, but upside potential open-ended

### 19. Beware of Trades Borne of Euphoria

- Caution against placing impulsive trades influenced by being caught up in market hysteria
- Excessive euphoria in market should be seen as cautionary flag of potential impending reversal

### 20. If You Are on the Right Side of Euphoria or Panic, Lighten Up

- Parabolic price moves in either direction tend to end abruptly and sharply
- If fortunate to be on right side of market where price move turns near vertical, consider scaling out while trend still moving in your direction
- If you would be petrified to be on other side of market, probably good sign you should be lightening position

### 21. Staring at the Screen All Day Can Be Expensive

- **Clark**: watching every tick can lead to both overtrading and increased chance of liquidating good positions
- Advises finding more productive use of time to avoid pitfalls of watching market too closely

### 22. Just Because You've Heard It 100 Times Doesn't Make It Less Important: Risk Control Is Critical

**Risk control strategies mentioned by traders:**

- **Risk limits on individual trades**: Many traders risk only small percentage of assets under management on any single trade
  - **Ramsey**: only risks loss of ~0.1% on any individual trade
  - Relatively close stop at trade inception while allowing wider stop relative to prevailing prices after profit margin established is effective risk management approach

- **Exposure reduction thresholds**: BlueCrest discretionary strategy contained worst drawdown to under 5% in more than decade despite managing double-digit billions
  - **Key**: firm's exposure reduction rules
  - **Michael Platt** (BlueCrest CEO): restricts discretionary traders to 3% loss limit (from starting allocation) before exposure allocation cut in half
  - Another 3% loss leads to removal of trader's entire allocation
  - Rules severely limit loss any trader can realize from starting allocation
  - As traders register gains, can increase risk levels because original exposure reduction thresholds remain unchanged for year
  - Upside potential open-ended, downside risk severely curtailed
  - Barring huge overnight gaps in market, larger losses can only occur through surrender of year-to-date profits rather than losses of original capital
  - **Benedict**: similar philosophy. Any time approaches 2.5% loss in given month, significantly reduces net exposure and continues trading in smaller size until loss recovered. Severely constrains potential loss in any given month.

- **Position size adjustments for changes in volatility**: 2008 examples
  - **Woodriff** and **Clark** both cut exposure levels by approximately factor of four in response to steep increase in volatility

- **Trade-dependent risk controls**: Some trades inherently risk-constrained, others have open-ended risk
  - **Thorp example**: For statistical arbitrage trades with well-defined maximum theoretical risk, didn't consider reducing exposure if position went against him
  - For trend-following strategy (directional trades with open-ended risk), made exposure reduction on drawdowns part of methodology

### 23. Don't Try to Be 100 Percent Right

- Almost every trader has experienced market moving against position sufficiently to raise significant concern about potential additional loss while still believing position correct
- Staying in trade risks uncomfortably large loss; liquidating risks abandoning good position at nearly worst possible point
- **Vidich advice**: instead of all-or-nothing decision, liquidate part of position
- Taking partial loss much easier than liquidating entire position
- Avoids possibility of riding entire position for large loss
- Preserves potential for partial recovery if market turns around

### 24. Protective Stops Need to Be Consistent with the Trade Analysis

- **O'Shea**: too many traders set stops based on pain threshold rather than points that disprove trade premise
- Because traders can't stand pain of larger loss, tend to set stops too close—at point where would still believe in trade
- Tendency for traders to try to repeatedly reenter trade after being stopped out
- Potentially leads to multiple losses which cumulatively can be larger than single loss that would have occurred with wider stop originally set at meaningful level
- **Advice**: Traders should first decide at what price they would believe trade is wrong, then set stop accordingly
- If implied loss to stop point uncomfortably large, position size should be reduced commensurately
- Using this approach, if market reaches stop point, will be consistent with demonstrating original trade idea was wrong

### 25. Constraining Monthly Losses Is Only a Good Idea if It Is Consistent with the Trading Strategy

- Tightly constraining monthly losses is prudent action for many traders
- **But for investors with long-term perspective, monthly loss constraints can be detrimental**
- **Taylor**: if strong conviction that stock will move much higher over long term, cutting exposure on interim weakness to limit depth of monthly loss would be mistake
- **Greenblatt**: value investors must maintain longer-term perspective and not be swayed by interim losses, providing fundamentals haven't changed
- For longer-term investors like Taylor and Greenblatt, monthly loss constraints would be in conflict with strategy

### 26. The Power of Diversification

- **Dalio**: calls diversification the "Holy Grail of investing"
- If assets truly uncorrelated, diversification could improve return/risk by as much as factor of 5:1

### 27. Correlation Can Be Misleading

- Being cognizant of correlation between different markets crucial to avoiding excessive risk
- **But**: correlation measures *past* price relationships
- Only relevant if reason to believe past correlation is reasonable proxy for future correlation
- Some market correlations stable, but others can vary widely and even change sign
- Stocks and bonds sometimes move in same direction and sometimes move inversely
- If correlation used during such transition period, can be worse than no information at all—can lead to exact wrong conclusions about future price relationships and risk

### 28. The Price Action in Related Markets Can Sometimes Provide Important Trading Clues

- For some traders (**Benedict**, **Ramsey**), interaction of price movements in related markets is critical input in trade decision process
- No set rules in how such price action should be interpreted
- Sometimes divergences between related markets can be important signals
<!-- pp. 421-440 -->

## Forty Market Wizard Lessons (Continued)

### 29. Markets Behave Differently in Different Environments

- Fundamental analysis assuming static relationships between economic variables and prices is doomed to failure
- **Ray Dalio**: Same fundamental conditions and government actions have different price consequences in deleveraging vs. recession environments
- Markets operate under different regimes—relationships that hold in one environment break down in another

### 30. Pay Attention to How the Market Responds to News

- Counter-to-anticipated response more meaningful than the news itself
- **Platt trade example**: Continuing stream of adverse news, repeatedly expected losses, yet market didn't move against him
- Read market's inability to respond as confirmation—quadrupled position into one of his biggest winners
- Price action reveals what market truly thinks vs. what news suggests it should think

### 31. Major Fundamental Events May Often Be Followed by Counterintuitive Price Movements

- **Dalio's two critical early career events**: U.S. gold standard abandonment (1971) followed by huge market rally; Mexican default (1982) followed by rally
- Two explanations for seemingly paradoxical behavior:
  - **First**: Major events often fully anticipated and discounted, or even overdiscounted
  - **Second**: Bearish fundamental development may spur government actions with greater market impact than event itself
- Government response can overwhelm the original bearish catalyst

### 32. Binary Outcome Situations Provide Excellent Option Buying Opportunities

- Option pricing models assume large price movements are unlikely
- When fundamentals suggest significant potential for large gain or loss, option prices fail to reflect abnormally large probability
- Options become mispriced when reality diverges from model assumptions
- Examples: **Greenblatt's Wells Fargo** option trade, **Mai's Capital One** option trade
- Look for situations where binary outcomes possible but not priced in

### 33. A Stock Can Be Well-Priced Even if It Has Already Gone Up a Lot

- Traders miss best opportunities by refusing to buy stocks that have already experienced large upmoves
- What matters: how well stock is priced relative to *future* prospects, not past price movement
- **Taylor's largest holding**: Apple had already seen large price advance—prior gain kept many investors away despite excellent fundamentals
- In Taylor's view, amount of prior price gain was irrelevant—stock still priced cheap based on earnings projections
- Price vs. value distinction critical

### 34. Don't Make Trading Decisions Based on Where You Bought (or Sold) a Stock

- Market doesn't care where you entered your position
- **Vidich example**: Stock fell all the way back to his entry point—just got out, didn't let entry level affect the decision
- Your purchase price is psychologically meaningful but economically irrelevant
- Evaluate position based on current outlook, not sunk cost

### 35. Potential New Revenue Sources More Than a Year Out May Not Be Reflected in Current Stock Price

- **Claugus**: Looks for situations where company will recognize new revenue sources one or more years out
- Future potential earnings frequently not adequately discounted—or discounted at all—by current stock price
- Market myopia creates opportunities in companies with long-dated catalysts
- Time horizon mismatch between company development and market pricing

### 36. Value Investing Works

- **Greenblatt** demonstrated value investing works through long career and rigorous computer-based research
- Catch: value investing works over long term, but has periods of poor performance
- Periodic underperformance is actually *the reason* value investing maintains its edge
- If it worked all the time, would attract enough followers so edge would disappear
- Long-term character of efficacy requires value investors to have similar long-term perspective
- Avoid inconsistencies between methodology and trading decisions
- Must withstand periods when approach out of favor

### 37. The Efficient Market Hypothesis Provides an Inaccurate Model of How the Market Really Works

- Prices not always near fair value—sometimes much too high, sometimes much too low
- **Greenblatt quotes Benjamin Graham metaphor**: Market like highly erratic business partner
- Partner sometimes willing to sell shares at absurdly low prices, sometimes willing to buy at ridiculously high prices
- Trader should take advantage of bouts of emotional irrationality by market
- Corollary: value investor typically seller during euphoria, buyer during panics
- To hold fundamentally justified value positions through market panics requires long-term perspective
- EMH assumes rational pricing; reality shows persistent mispricing driven by emotion

### 38. It Is Usually a Mistake for a Manager to Alter Investment Decisions or Process to Better Fit Investor Demands

- **Greenblatt to students**: "You are setting yourself up for failure if you invest differently than you want to in order to please investors"
- **Taylor**: "I am trying to stop caring about what my clients think"
- Changing approach to accommodate investor preferences undermines methodology
- Stay true to process even when clients uncomfortable
- Client demands often push toward exactly wrong behavior (e.g., buying what's popular, selling what's working)

### 39. Volatility and Risk Are Not Synonymous

- Low volatility does not imply low risk; high volatility does not imply high risk
- Investments subject to sporadic large risks may exhibit low volatility if risk event not present in existing track record
- **Example**: Selling out-of-the-money options can exhibit low volatility if no large, abrupt moves—but at risk of asymptotically increasing losses in event of sudden, steep selloff
- **Mai**: High volatility because of occasional very large gains—not a risk factor most investors would associate with risk or consider undesirable
- Strictly curtailed risk because of asymmetric structure of trades
- Some strategies (option selling) have low volatility and large, open-ended risk
- Other strategies (Mai's) have high volatility and constrained risk
- Conventional risk metrics misleading

### 40. It Is a Mistake to Select Managers Based Solely on Past Performance

- **Greenblatt cites empirical studies**: Past performance of managers has no predictive value for future performance
- Single factor that overwhelmingly determines how investors choose investments—past returns—has no efficacy
- **Greenblatt advises**: Choose managers based on their *process* rather than past returns
- Related point: Investors often equate manager performance in given year with manager skill
- Sometimes more skilled managers underperform because they refuse to participate in market bubbles
- **Best performers during bubbles often most imprudent**, not most skilled
- **Taylor underperformed in 1999**: Thought it ridiculous to buy tech stocks at inflated levels
- Same investment decision instrumental to large outperformance in subsequent years when stocks witnessed prolonged, massive decline
- Past performance can sometimes be inverse indicator
- Short-term underperformance may reflect discipline, not weakness

---

## Epilogue

### Jack Schwager's Reflections

- Interview and writing process solidified principles important to trading success
- **Personal trading example** (summer interview time): Stock market approaching high end of long-term range, expected rally to fail
- Positioned short stock index futures
- Government released extremely bearish employment report—market initially sold off sharply
- "Perfect," thought Schwager—but by end of day, nearly recovered entire loss, ending week near recent high
- From short-term perspective: terrible price action
- Prepared to cover most position when market opened Sunday night
- Sunday night market opened lower
- **Immediately thought of Marty Schwartz's advice** from first *Market Wizards*: "If you're very nervous about a position overnight, especially over weekend, and you're able to get out at much better price than you thought when market trades, you're usually better off staying with position"
- Did stay with position—saved a lot of money as market proceeded to move sharply lower in ensuing weeks

### Personal Lessons from Interviews

- Each trader must draw personal insights from interviews depending on own trading style
- All traders can draw important lessons from advice and comments regardless of approach
- Relevant interviews and advice different for each reader
- **Personal example**: **Jimmy Balodimas** interview—basic approach radically different from Schwager's
- Balodimas influenced Schwager to trade more around positions (dynamic vs. static process)
- More in tune with Schwager's natural inclinations
- **Balodimas comment**: "I always take some money off the table when the market is in my favor" resonated
- Some trades that went nowhere ended up generating net profits

### Impact of Market Wizards Series

- Many people told Schwager original *Market Wizards* books changed careers and lives
- Heard from professional managers and numerous conference attendees
- Never know whether life-changing impact for better
- **Physician example**: Dropped career to become trader after reading book—Schwager felt guilty about depriving world of doctor in exchange for one more trader
- Ironic: One person whose life changed was Schwager's own son, **Zachary**
- Had direct impact on content of this book
- Don't know if change for better or worse—proverbial road not taken remains forever unseen
- Appropriate to end with personal reflections on message and influence of book and predecessors
- Offering view from perspective of someone discovering and entering world of trading

---

## Zachary Schwager's Reflections

### Early Life and Introduction to Trading

- **Age 8**: "Bring your child to work" day at father's office
- Father called him over for game: cycle through charts, guess whether next move up or down
- Wasn't game at all—was experiment
- **Father's theory**: Some individuals naturally gifted traders with instinctive ability to recognize and predict visual price patterns
- Five charts into game, father concluded Zachary not one of these individuals
- Years before would look at another chart

### Meeting John Bender

- **Junior year of high school**: Would meet first Market Wizard, **John Bender**
- Suggested to father they take trip before college
- Father always game for adventure—several years earlier disappeared on hike up Mount Temple in Canadian Rockies
- Came back 12 hours later with frostbite, having decided to summit mountain instead
- **John Bender**: Just retired from trading, used gains to buy up thousands of acres of Costa Rican rain forest
- Invited to stay at guesthouse on reserve

### Visit to Costa Rica

- Arranged SUV to drive four hours from San Jose up to Bender's reserve in rain forest
- Car made way up winding, single-lane dirt road, top with clearing with two heavily armed men
- Reserve patrolled by guards to prevent poaching
- Property had three residences (one under construction) set on large, grassy plateau
- Existing main house where Bender resided with wife Ann while building spectacular, multilevel, 360-degree-view dream house on edge of plateau
- Settled into third dwelling (guesthouse), agreed to meet Bender for drink
- **Bender on porch overlooking rain forest**: Talked for hours as sun set over edge of rain forest
- Led most of conversation—had lots of energy, as if had so much to say and waiting for right person to talk to
- Conversation ranged from paradoxes in quantum physics experiments to Bender's particular disgust for one fund manager he insisted was fraud
- Wouldn't hear that manager's name again for nine years, when financial crisis exposed what Bender had known: **Bernie Madoff was a fraud**

### College and Career Decision

- College quickly approaching
- Went to father's office to seek advice on major
- Embarrassing: At this point had still not read *Market Wizards*
- No involvement with markets; father never pushed anyone toward his own desires
- Told father wanted to be doctor
- **Father's response**: "I don't think that's a very good fit"
- Father always gives truth, beginning sentence with awkward chuckle to hide discomfort when candor requires imparting opinion he knows you don't want to hear
- Didn't take advice immediately, but wasn't long into first year when realized father right
- More of creative type; being doctor probably not good fit
- Switched to film school in New York

### First Trading Experience

- To help spark interest in investing, father given $500 Ameritrade account
- Found few recommendations online, bought three stocks
- Two climbed higher; third (CSX) hovered in range somewhere between $30 and $40
- Called father, ready to impress with insight
- Having noted stock's trading pattern, told him planned to sell near $40, then buy back near $30
- **Father's response**: "Yeah, people do that"—not impressed, chuckled
- Two years later account up over $2,000
- Recognized knew remarkably little about stock market, assumed probably just been lucky
- Liquidated portfolio, bought film camera

### Father's Trading Expo Talk

- Father coming to New York to give talk at trading expo
- Extended invitation, cautiously accepted
- Pulled only collared shirt from bottom of closet, made way to Hilton Times Square
- Everyone wearing suits, instantly felt uncomfortable
- Mother (whom father refers to as his best long-term trade) already seated
- Walked over, sat next to her
- Greeted with favorite comment: "You're such a handsome boy, but nobody would ever know by the way you are dressed"
- Room filled up; father walked to podium
- Everyone extremely excited to hear what he had to say
- Sank into seat, hoped would understand enough to say something nice when over
- Didn't know moment would change rest of life

### Father's Three Key Insights

- Father began to speak—waited for words to drift beyond realm of comprehension, but moment never came
- **Einstein quote**: "Any intelligent fool can make things bigger, more complex, and more violent. It takes a touch of genius—and a lot of courage—to move in the opposite direction"
- Father always had ability and desire to take complex ideas and boil them down to simplest forms
- Talk based on important lessons uncovered in interviews with world's top traders
- **Three key insights resonated**, changed previous conceptions about trading:

**1. Trading is not reserved for the world's most elite**
- Traders interviewed came from various backgrounds
- No correlation between trading success and school or prior occupation
- Commonality traced to hard work and determination, desire to unlock puzzle of market
- All shared aspiration to avoid psychological impediments preventing most people from winning in markets

**2. Trading is not just a science, but also an art**
- Even traders using purely systematic approach still engaged in creative thinking
- None stepped into already working formula; nobody handed blueprint
- Success built on backbone of ability to discover what others overlooked

**3. There is no single right way to make money**
- Those who succeed do so because they find what works for them
- Trying to replicate someone else's method almost always results in failure
- All successful traders have own methodology, approach that makes sense to them and comfortable with

### Question-and-Answer Session

- Talk concluded with Q&A
- Industry professionals had questions very similar to Zachary's own
- Realized not as much divided them as originally assumed
- All wanted to know and understand more, including father (what set him out on quest to interview Market Wizards years earlier)

### Working with Father on Book

- Had honor of working with father on this book
- Not meant to imply did much at all—simply privilege of sharing impressions and suggestions after reading each chapter
- Amount of work father puts into books incredible
- Amazed at time it takes to go through many hours of tapes to formulate each chapter
- People often tell father he's great interviewer, to which he frequently replies: "I am a horrible interviewer, but I am an excellent editor"
- Only latter half true
- Father has natural ability to pull best out of anybody
- Manages to ask all questions you can think of and then all ones he can think of
- Working with father on book one of greatest learning experiences

### Future Path

- Beyond this book, quite pleased to say won't be last time able to pick father's brain for market knowledge
- After watching him speak at trading expo, dropped out of film school, went off to get bachelor's degree in finance
- Now work as junior trader at **First New York Securities**
- No idea what future holds or whether will be successful at trading in long run
- Do know knowledge gained from experience will serve wherever life takes

### Personal Perspective on Father

- Couple months ago, out for happy hour with associates
- One asked: "Do you think that because of your dad you have a lot to live up to as a trader?"
- Replied: "It would be far easier to be as successful as my dad in trading than to be as successful as he is on a human level"
- **Father**: One of kindest, humblest, and most generous people ever come across
- Would much rather be as great a person as he is than to be as successful as he is

