## Appendix A: The Gain to Pain Ratio

### Performance Measurement Beyond Return

- Return only meaningful relative to risk required to get it
- Could always get higher return by using leverage—doesn't mean better performance
- **Gain to Pain ratio (GPR)**: Sum of all monthly returns divided by absolute value of sum of all monthly losses
- Performance measure indicates ratio of cumulative net gain to cumulative loss realized to achieve that gain
- **Example**: GPR of 1.0 would imply on average, investor would experience equal amount of monthly losses to *net* amount gained
- If average return per year 12% (arithmetic, not compounded), average amount of monthly losses per year would also sum to 12%
- GPR penalizes all losses in proportion to their size
- Upside volatility beneficial because only impacts return portion of ratio
- Sharpe ratio (most widely used return/risk measure) penalizes upside volatility
- **Rough guideline for liquid strategies**: Any GPR above 1.0 very good; GPR above 1.5 excellent

### Origin and Relation to Other Metrics

- GPR performance statistic Schwager using for many years
- Not aware of prior use, though term sometimes used as generic reference for return/risk measures or return/drawdown measure
- Similar to "profit factor" (commonly used statistic in evaluating trading systems)
- **Profit factor**: Sum of all profitable trades divided by absolute value of sum of all losing trades
- Profit factor applied to trades; GPR applied to interval (e.g., monthly) returns
- Algebraically: If profit factor calculation applied to monthly returns, profit factor would equal GPR + 1 and provide same performance ordering as GPR
- **For quantitatively oriented readers**: Omega function evaluated at zero also equal to GPR + 1

---

## Appendix B: Options—Understanding the Basics

### Call and Put Options Defined

- **Call option**: Provides buyer right (not obligation) to purchase underlying item at specified price (**strike/exercise price**) any time up to and including **expiration date**
- **Put option**: Provides buyer right (not obligation) to sell underlying item at strike price any time prior to expiration
- Buying put = bearish trade; selling put = bullish trade
- Price of option called **premium**
- **Example**: IBM April 210 call gives purchaser right to buy 100 shares of IBM at $210 per share any time during life of option

### Call Option Mechanics

- Call buyer seeks profit from anticipated price rise by locking in specified purchase price
- Maximum possible loss = dollar amount of premium paid for option
- Maximum loss occurs on option held until expiration if strike price above prevailing market price
- **Example**: If IBM trading at $205 when 210 option expired, option expires worthless
- If at expiration price of underlying above strike, option has value and will be exercised
- However, if difference between market price and strike less than premium paid, trade still loss
- For net profit: Difference between market price and strike must exceed premium paid when call purchased (after adjusting for commission)
- Higher market price, greater resulting profit

### Put Option Mechanics

- Put buyer seeks profit from anticipated price decline by locking in sales price
- Maximum possible loss limited to dollar amount of premium paid
- For put held until expiration, trade shows net profit if strike price exceeded market price by amount greater than premium of put at purchase (after commission)

### Option Seller Risk/Reward

- Option buyer has limited risk, unlimited potential gain
- Reverse true for seller
- **Option seller (writer)**: Receives dollar value of premium in return for undertaking obligation to assume opposite position *at strike price* if option exercised
- **Example**: If call exercised, seller must assume short position in underlying market at strike price (since buyer assumes long position at that price by exercising)

### Selling Calls and Puts

- **Call seller**: Seeks profit from anticipated sideways to modestly declining market—premium earned most attractive trading opportunity
- If expected large price decline, better off going short underlying market or buying put (trades with open-ended profit potential)
- **Put seller**: Seeks profit from anticipated sideways to modestly rising market

### Probability Considerations

- Option buyer accepts large probability of small loss in return for small probability of large gain
- Option seller accepts small probability of large loss in exchange for large probability of small gain
- Probability must be taken into account alongside theoretical risk/reward

### Option Premium Components

- **Premium = intrinsic value + time value**
- **Intrinsic value of call**: Amount by which current market price above strike price
- **Intrinsic value of put**: Amount by which current market price below strike price
- Intrinsic value = part of premium that could be realized if option exercised at current market price
- Intrinsic value serves as floor price for option
- Why? If premium less than intrinsic value, trader could buy and exercise option, immediately offset resulting market position, realizing net gain (assuming covers at least transaction costs)

### Option Terminology

- **In-the-money options**: Have intrinsic value (calls with strikes below market price; puts with strikes above market price)
- **Out-of-the-money options**: Have no intrinsic value
- **At-the-money options**: Strike price closest to market price

### Time Value

- Out-of-the-money option (intrinsic value = 0) still has value because of possibility market price will move beyond strike prior to expiration
- In-the-money option value greater than intrinsic value because if priced at intrinsic value, position in option always preferred to position in underlying market
- Why? Both option and market position gain equally in event of favorable price movement, but option's maximum loss limited
- Portion of premium exceeding intrinsic value called **time value**

### Factors Influencing Time Value

**1. Relationship between strike and market price**
- Deeply out-of-the-money options: Little time value (unlikely market price will move to strike or beyond prior to expiration)
- Deeply in-the-money options: Little time value (positions very similar to underlying market—both gain and lose equivalent amounts for all but extremely adverse price move)
- For deeply in-the-money option, fact that risk is limited not worth very much because strike price so far from prevailing market price

**2. Time remaining until expiration**
- More time remaining, greater value of option
- Longer life span increases probability of intrinsic value increasing by any specified amount prior to expiration

**3. Volatility**
- Time value varies directly with estimated **volatility** (measure of degree of price variability) of underlying market for remaining life span
- Greater volatility raises probability of intrinsic value increasing by any specified amount prior to expiration
- Greater volatility, greater probable price range of market

### Implied Volatility vs. Realized Volatility

- Volatility extremely important factor in determining option premium values
- Future volatility of market never precisely known until after the fact
- Time remaining until expiration and relationship between current market price and strike can be exactly specified
- Thus volatility must always be estimated on basis of *historical volatility* data
- **Implied volatility**: Future volatility estimate implied by market prices (option premiums)
- May be higher or lower than historical volatility

### Options Tend to Be Priced High

- On average, tendency for implied volatility to be higher than subsequent *realized volatility* of market till options' expiration
- Options tend to be priced a little high
- Extra premium necessary to induce option sellers to take open-ended risk of providing price insurance to option buyers
- Situation analogous to home insurance premiums priced at levels providing profit margin to insurance companies—otherwise would have no incentive to assume open-ended risk

*This appendix originally published in Market Wizards (1989).*

